DPC: Three people were killed in confrontations with the police in Navarrete in the northern province of Santiago, and one in the city of San Francisco de Macor?s, the capital of the northern Duarte province, in the Dominican Republic. The deaths happened during anti-government protests, organised by the Broad Popular Front (Frente Amplio Popular: FALPO), staged between 21 and 24 October. The protests in the Santiago and Duarte provinces were driven by a variety of demands against incumbent president Danilo Medina ranging from increased wages to better infrastructure, accountability for government officials, and improved security in the country. Economic hardships and mounting dissatisfaction over large-scale immigration from Haiti and government corruption have increased social discontent, as have the prolonged power blackouts and high prices of fuel, public transportation, and food. Protests were also notably held by a variety of groups including local communities, farmers, and students, as well as anti-corruption activists. The protests forced authorities to suspend classes from state university Universidad Aut?noma de Santo Domingo, San Francisco de Macor?s, and in other state schools because of fears of an escalation of disorder (jane's intelligence weekly). FOUR people were wounded in violent clashes which broke out between employees of a mining company and opponents of a new mining project in an unspecified location in the Domnican Republic's Monse?or Nouel province on 9 October, the Latin American Herald Tribune reported (jane's).

DPC since September 2013: civil unrest against gov including teachers strike, anti-mining protest:        DPC in September: Unions, students, and left-wing organisations in Mexico City have organised protests against the government of President Enrique Pe?a Nieto over recent weeks. Mining firms operating in Mexico face increased civil unrest and extortion risks, while the government is also likely to increase tax rates. Local communities and NGOs are increasingly voicing their opposition to the sector, which are motivated by environmental concerns, local demands for prior consultation, compensation, social investments, and ideological factors. The level of anti-mining sentiment in Mexico is particularly high in the state of Morelos, but also extends to other states such as Baja California, Guerrero, Michoac?n, Oaxaca, Puebla, San Luis Potos?, and Zacatecas. IC: A Guatemalan national was shot and killed by the Belizean Defence Forces (BDF) in the country's Chiquibul national park on 29 March. a shoot-out took place between a Belizean joint patrol - comprising the BDF and police officers - and a group of armed Guatemalan civilians who had crossed into Belizean territory. Incidents of this nature are not uncommon in the border zone, and there have been at least seven such shootings - resulting in four deaths - since 2011. This is partly attributable to uncertainty over the border itself, which is not properly demarcated as a result of a longstanding territorial dispute between Belize and Guatemala over a 12,700 sq km zone; the area is currently administered by Belize. This shooting does not raise the risks of armed conflict between Belize and Guatemala, which remain low even though diplomatic friction will heighten in the short term. Indeed, the Belizean and Guatemalan authorities yesterday issued a joint statement affirming their commitment to the maintenance of peace and friendly relations (intelligence weekly, April 1).

College Students Protest Against Elections Results -- Tegucigalpa El Heraldo.hn reports that college students protested in the capital city yesterday rejecting the results in the general elections that show the National Party as the victor. notes: DPC: Media reports published on 12 May showed Individuals in Comayag?ela protesting against the high cost of fuel by burning tyres to block streets.This is a relatively new form of public demonstration in the fight against rising energy prices in Honduras. In first quarter of 2014, public and private employees have opposed energy price increases. In Tegucigalpa, hospital workers protested over high costs that left ambulances without petrol. Over the same period, state-run National Electric Energy Company (Empresa Nacional de Energia Electrica: ENEE) employees have staged demonstrations over pricing, taxation, and subsidies. ENEE's trade union STENEE has also promised to continue strikes over the next year over liberalisation plans (jane's intelligence weekly, May 14).  Members and supporters of the largest Honduran opposition party in Congress, Liberty and Refoundation (Liberdad y Refundaci?n: LIBRE), protested outside Congress on 14 May. The protest followed the forced eviction - using tear gas and batons - of members of LIBRE from Congress by military police on 13 May. Those evicted included LIBRE leader and former president Manuel Zelaya (2006-09) and his wife, former presidential candidate Xiomara Castro. Members of the LIBRE party had been protesting inside congress, accusing the ruling National Party (Partido National: PN) of denying the opposition the opportunity to speak. Around 600 protesters were involved in the protest outside the building, while around 250 managed to enter the chamber (jane's intelligence weekly, May 16). IC: Jane's report: Nicaragua's Congress on 26 November approved the entry of US and Russian troops into the country under a remit that will include training and assisting Nicaraguan forces in counter-drugs operations. This initiative is likely to enhance Nicaragua's counter crime capabilities, which in turn has the potential to improve security along the Caribbean coast, which is of commercial interest in terms of fishing, oil exploration, and the building of the proposed transoceanic canal. It also raises the risks of diplomatic fallout between Nicaragua and Colombia - although escalation to the point of conflict is likely to be mitigated by close US-Colombia relations. In this regard, Nicaragua on 27 November launched a new case against Colombia at the International Court of Justice (ICJ) accusing the South American country of not adhering to the court's November 2012 decision that granted previously Colombian-held maritime territory to Nicaragua. Colombia subsequently recalled its ambassador from Nicaragua. There is a risk of accidental infractions in the disputed maritime zone, although this will most likely be limited to the temporary detention of local/artisan fishing boats (jane's, http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-25131485). I tend to code this as IC, because there's hightened tension between the two countries,  but let's recheck next month.

DPC: DPC in Colombia started in June 2013.   On July 3, jane's reported: "At least four people have been killed during protest action in the last three weeks, which has included road blockades and clashes between demonstrators and police." Protesters described as "landless farmers". On August 3 jane's reported: "The Colombian authorities yesterday (8 August) imposed a curfew on the town of Zaragoza in the northern department of Antioquia following ongoing protest action by small-scale or artisan miners."  On Aug 20, jane's reported: "A nationwide strike that began yesterday (19 August) and remains ongoing today (20 August), raises the risk of organised civil unrest in Colombia in the one year outlook. The strike brought together various pressure groups including labour federations, agricultural producers, coffee growers, health workers, landless farmers, lorry drivers, miners, and students; all of whom have specific albeit overlapping grievances."  In June crisis watch reported: "Protests over coca eradication and peasants reservations turned violent in Norte de Santander?s Catatumbo region; 4 people killed".   In July crisis watch reported: "Tensions between peasant communities and security forces in Norte de Santander continued, 4 protester deaths reported; UNOHCHR 15 July criticised govt for alleged ?excessive? use of force". In Aug  Crisis watch reported: "Santos 30 Aug ordered 50,000 military to guarantee mobility throughout country in reaction to violent protests 29 Aug which media said left 5 dead and 250 injured. 2-month peasant strike in Catatumbo region stopped after 2 Aug agreement to hold negotiations; first agreement on drug eradication reached 28 Aug".  I therefore suggest coding DPC 1 in June, July, and August. recheck next month.
insnotes: FARC and ELN insurgencies continued: 13th cycle of govt-FARC peace negotiations ended 28 Aug with discussions still centred on political participation. Talks had been suspended 23-25 Aug as FARC studied implications of 22 Aug govt draft legislation to allow referendum on possible peace agreement to coincide with 2014 national elections.
dpcnotes: Protests by peasant communities

notes: IC: Colombia will maintain a full military presence in the disputed maritime zone with Nicaragua, Colombian Minister of Defence Juan Carlos Pinz?n stated on 11 September. The announcement follows a heightening of tensions between Colombia and Nicaragua this week after Colombian president Juan Manuel Santos announced on 9 September that his government would not observe a November 2012 ruling by the International Court of Justice (ICJ) to alter the Colombia-Nicaragua maritime boundary (jane's). Jane's forecasts that "Regional war risks remain low despite the heightening of bilateral tensions. " Recheck next month.                       INS: New cycle of govt-FARC peace negotiations ended 19 Sept amid increasing tensions; talks to resume 3 Oct. President Santos 24 Sept said before UNGA peace will not lead to impunity for serious crimes, also called for faster negotiation results as ?time for decisions? had come. In reaction, FARC leader Timochenko 25 Sept slammed Santos for supposedly ?unilaterally imposing? restrictions on talks. Security forces 25 Sept killed high-ranking member of FARC?s Daniel Aldana mobile column in Tumaco, Nari?o. VP Garz?n 9 Sept announced peace talks with ELN would begin ?over next days and in different place to Havana?, but new setback 10 Sept when ELN allegedly kidnapped 3 pipeline workers in Saravena, Arauca. ELN 30 Sept reaffirmed willingness to participate in peace talks (crisis watch).                    DPC: Santos 4 Sept announced cabinet reshuffle, replacing inter alia embattled interior and agriculture ministers; 12 Sept presented ?National Agrarian Pact? to confront agrarian crisis, but initiative rejected by peasant grassroots. Amid social protests, Santos approval ratings down to 21%. Former President Uribe 16 Sept announced he will run as head of list for Senate in March 2014 elections (crisis watch). ongoing protests and strike action across the country by numerous sectors (including agricultural producers and miners), which have damaged political support for Santos's government (jane's).
insnotes: FARC and ELN insurgencies continued.
dpcnotes: Agrarian crisis. Peasant and miners protest continued.
icnotes: Colombia-Nicaragua maritime zone dispute

notes: IC: No reports of hightened tension between Nicaragua and Colombia (crisis watch, jane's, bbc, guardian, opensource).                       INS: 16th round of govt-FARC peace talks started 23 Oct with discussions still centred on political participation. With 2014 electoral cycle approaching fast, President Santos 8 Oct discussed with senators and representatives of his party whether to pause, continue or end negotiations, with majority of Congress supporting continuation of talks but parties yet to discuss option in Havana. Amid increased FARC attacks on military targets and energy infrastructure mainly in E and SE, Santos 9 Oct launched large-scale counter-insurgency initiative targeted at FARC?s southern strongholds; denied contradiction with peace talks. FARC released former U.S. marine Kevin Scott Sutay 27 Oct after 4 months? captivity. ELN 14 Oct said its delegation for exploratory talks with govt has been ?ready? for a year, but process has not gone beyond ?attempts to start?. Regional leader of New Illegal Armed Group Urabe?os in Norte de Santander department ?El Mico? surrendered and was captured alongside 17 members 23 Oct (crisis watch, jane's).                     DPC: Agrarian crisis. Peasant and miners protest continued. Protests by Colombia's indigenous communities, which started on 14 October, escalated on 17 October after the protesters set up road blocks, forcing police to intervene. The demonstrations, organised by Colombia's Indigenous People Organisation (Organizaci?n Nacional Ind?gena de Colombia: ONIC), have been staged to demand land restitution and an end to illegal mining operations in their territory (jane's, Oct 18).  IN A statement issued on 18 October, Colombian authorities confirmed that anti-government protesters were holding seven security force personnel hostage in two separate locations in the Belen de Umbria area of Risaralda department and in an unspecified location in Cauca department, Colombia Reports reported (jane's) .  STUDENT protesters engaged in violent clashes with security forces and riot police in the Pedagogical University in an unspecified location in Colombia?s Antioquia department on 22 October, resulting in no reported casualties, Caracol Radio reported (jane's).
insnotes: FARC and ELN insurgencies continued.
dpcnotes: Agrarian crisis. Peasant and miners protest continued.

notes: IC: Jane's report: Nicaragua's Congress on 26 November approved the entry of US and Russian troops into the country under a remit that will include training and assisting Nicaraguan forces in counter-drugs operations. This initiative is likely to enhance Nicaragua's counter crime capabilities, which in turn has the potential to improve security along the Caribbean coast, which is of commercial interest in terms of fishing, oil exploration, and the building of the proposed transoceanic canal. It also raises the risks of diplomatic fallout between Nicaragua and Colombia - although escalation to the point of conflict is likely to be mitigated by close US-Colombia relations. In this regard, Nicaragua on 27 November launched a new case against Colombia at the International Court of Justice (ICJ) accusing the South American country of not adhering to the court's November 2012 decision that granted previously Colombian-held maritime territory to Nicaragua. Colombia subsequently recalled its ambassador from Nicaragua. There is a risk of accidental infractions in the disputed maritime zone, although this will most likely be limited to the temporary detention of local/artisan fishing boats (jane's, http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-25131485). I tend to code this as IC, because there's hightened tension between the two countries,  but let's recheck next month.                             INS: FARC and ELN insurgencies continued. Significant step forward in govt-FARC peace talks 6 Nov with announcement of partial agreement on political participation, 2nd of 5 agenda issues; agreement calls for end in using arms in politics and democratic opening of political system. President Santos 26 Nov appointed Mar?a Paulina Riveros and Nigeria Renter?a to become first female lead negotiators. Talks resumed 28 Nov with discussions on issue of illegal drugs. Defence Minister Pinz?n 12 Nov revealed alleged FARC plans to kill former President Uribe, critical of talks, and Attorney General Eduardo Montealegre, strong  upporter of talks; FARC?s Southern Bloc 27 Nov denied plans. Hopes revived that progress in Havana could help overcome apparent impasse in attempts to start peace talks with National Liberation Army (ELN); ELN?s Central Command 11 Nov praised political participation accord as early ?Christmas gift?, but also said ?magic wand? needed to convert it into reality. ELN 4 Nov released 3 oil workers kidnapped in Arauca in Sept, 5 Nov announced plan to free engineer working for Chilean timber company held hostage since mid-2012. Military strike in Fortul (Arauca) 24 Nov killed at least 10 ELN members (crisis watch).                        DPC:  Agrarian crisis. Peasant and miners protest continued. THREE people were killed and at least two others were wounded during violent clashes between miners ? protesting evictions of miners by the government ? and police in the town of Buritica in Colombia?s Antioquia department on 22 November, El Espectador reported (jane's). OVER 1000 illegal miners ? protesting their eviction from the mining industry ? engaged in clashes with police in the town of Buritica in Colombia?s Antioquia department on 20 November, Caracol Radio reported. No casualties were reported (jane's).
insnotes: FARC and ELN insurgencies continued.
dpcnotes: Agrarian crisis. Peasant and miners protest continued.
icnotes: Colombia-Nicaragua maritime zone dispute

notes: INS: Janes':"The Ej?rcito de Liberaci?n Nacional (ELN), Colombia's second largest insurgent group, carried out an improvised explosive device (IED) attack on the Ca?o Lim?n Cove?as pipeline in northeast Colombia yesterday (1 January). The incident is the ELN's first offensive operation in 2014 and illustrates the ongoing high risk to oil infrastructure, particularly in north-east Colombia."    The attack follows the killing of six ELN insurgents by the Colombian military in the municipality of San Calixto in Norte de Santander on 31 December. Since the attack by ELN is a revenge attack due to an event in December 2013, I coded Insurgency as 1 although the event itself happened in Janurary, 2014. DPC: Janes': "Protests in central Bogot? against the controversial dismissal of Mayor Gustavo Petro. Petro, a former guerrilla leader and Colombia's most visible leftist politician, faces removal after the inspector-general in early December found him guilty of administrative mismanagement. In a move that is likely to incite further controversy, Colombia's electoral authorities last week confirmed that the requisite 350,000 signatures had been collected to stage a recall referendum on the mayor. In the meantime, demonstrations comprising tens of thousands of people have taken place in support of Petro, whose popularity has risen from to 47%, up from 32% in August, according to a poll by Gallup."      Although this protest is wide spread and political significant, it is not violent in nature and therefore I coded it 0.
insnotes: Violent attacks from ELN insurgency
dpcnotes: Protests in central Bogota against the controversial dismissal of Mayor Gustavo Petro who faces removal after the inspector-general in early December found him guilty of administrative mismanagement. notes: INS: 19th round of peace talks between govt and FARC ended 23 Jan; negotiations to restart 3 Feb; FARC 14 Jan published detailed proposal for state-funded ?National Programme to Substitute Illicit Uses of Coca, Poppy and Marijuana Crops?, drawing on ideas already formulated during ill-fated 2002 Cagu?n talks, including suspension of aerial fumigation, community-driven alternative development plans, creation of legal market for coca, poppy and marijuana crops. Month-long unilateral FARC ceasefire ended 15 Jan; violations occurred, but generally well-respected. 1 killed, over 60 injured in FARC motorcycle bomb attack in Pradera (Valle) 16 Jan; unusually strongly-worded Secretariat communiqu? 23 Jan acknowledged attack, expressed ?rejection and disapproval? for high civilian impact. Military reacted with offensive killing 27 FARC fighters and capturing 21 19-22 Jan (crisis watch).                             DPC: Prosecutor General Alejandro Ord??ez 13 Jan rejected appeal against Dec decision to remove Bogot? mayor Gustavo Petro from office; several Bogot? court decisions subsequently suspended removal, offering lifeline for Petro to stay in office until 2 March recall referendum (crisis watch). Reports of mass protest in Bogota on this issue in early January (http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-25692189,  http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-25741629, http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/10/bogota-mayor-gustavo-petro-removed). notes: INS:  22nd cycle of peace talks between govt and FARC ended 30 March; parties optimistic to conclude discussions on illegal drugs ?soon?. FARC 21 March acknowledged responsibility for earlier killing of 2 policemen in Tumaco (Nari?o), but 26 March refused to hand over perpetrators. National Liberation Army (ELN) 6 March liberated in Antioquia police official kidnapped in Feb; 17 March reiterated its willingness to engage in new talks. Santos 26 March said peace process had sufficiently matured to re-activate National Peace Council (crisis watch). Many reports of ELN and FARC activity in jane's.                          DPC: Congressional elections took place 9 March amid high abstention rate, allegations of fraud and election of 69 candidates allegedly linked to illegal armed actors, but relatively few security incidents overall. Polls brought no radical change in balance of political forces; preliminary results showed President Santos? ruling coalition lost clout but still boasts strong majority in Lower House (92/166 votes) and remains well positioned in Senate (47/102 votes); opposition Democratic Centre led by former President Uribe came 2nd in Senate (19 votes). Santos 19 March signed decree removing Bogot? mayor and former M-19 guerrilla Gustavo Petro from office, executing highly controversial decision of Inspector General; move came day after Inter American Human Rights Commission (IACHR) asked govt to suspend dismissal; govt argued IACHR measures non-binding (crisis watch). Social movements participating in ?National Agrarian Summit? 16 March threatened new strike for early May. Santos 6 March announced major security force intervention in Buenaventura (Valle) to combat escalating criminal violence (crisis watch). FOUR councilmen were threatened with death by unidentified militants and forced to leave their residence with their families within 24 hours in the town of San Jose de Alban in Colombia?s Narino department on 15 March, Colombia Reports reported (jane's). A COUNCILMAN was shot dead by an unidentified militant inside his residence in the town of San Jose de Alban in Colombia?s Narino department on 15 March, Colombia Reports reported (jane's). ONE bus driver was shot dead and nine civilians were wounded in clashes which broke out at protests against a change to the transportation system in the city of Cali in Colombia?s Valle del Cauca department on 19 March, Colombia Reports reported (jane's).                     IC: no reports of hightened tension with Nicaragua. Smooth away 2013 IC.
insnotes: FARC and ELN insurgencies continued.
dpcnotes: Tension between gov and opposition related to elections and removal of Bogota mayor, including violence. Agrarian crisis.

notes: INS: Govt, FARC representatives 16 May reached preliminary agreement on drug policies, 3rd issue under discussion in Havana peace talks; parties agreed, inter alia, on national crop substation program and demining initiative; first time FARC has implicitly recognised wider links to drug-economy. Agreement followed 16 May historic announcement of joint FARC/ELN unilateral ceasefire 20-28 May. ?scar Ivn Zuluaga, peace talks sceptic, won first round of presidential elections 25 May; faces incumbent President Santos in 15 June run-off. Turnout historically low at 40%. Video released 17 May showed Zuluaga apparently discussing ways to use classified military intelligence to undermine peace process; followed 6 May arrest of Zuluaga campaign aide for allegedly spying on Santos and FARC negotiator email accounts. Santos chief campaign manager resigned 5 May, accused of having received $12mn from notorious drug trafficker. Ombudsmans Office 12 May said some 2,500 indigenous people from High Baud? region (Choc?) displaced by fighting between ELN and NIAG Urabeos. Police 30 May arrested 46 NIAG Rastrojos members in Barranquilla, Atlantico dept (crisis watch). Many reports of FARC and ELN attacks in jane's.                                 DPC: Govt 8 May created national platform to discuss peasant demands established during March meeting of Agrarian Summit, end new wave of social protests; FARC 13 May praised grassroots organisations for achieving formidable triumph" (crisis watch).THREE police officers and an unspecified number of activists were wounded during armed clashes instigated by student protests outside the National University of Colombia in Colombias capital Bogota on 7 May, Colombia Reports and La Voz reported. Protests shut down major roads in the capital (jane's). DOZENS of protesters and police officers were wounded in armed clashes around several roadblocks, put up by protesters, in Colombias Huila department on 5 May, Colombia Reports reported. According to police sources, police forces were wounded in attack in which acid was used (jane's). Protest continued in June.
insnotes: FARC and ELN insurgencies continued.
dpcnotes: Students protest, agrarian crisis

DPC: Workers from state-owned steel producer SIDOR on 28 September lifted an 11 day strike they had been staging demanding better wages and government compliance with employment and social benefits established in the current collective agreement. The event is being interpreted by SUTISS workers as a victory against the government of incumbent president Nicol?s Maduro, who initially assumed a strong stance against some of its leaders calling them "counter-revolutionaries"  (jane's). However, no reports of widespread protest in Venezuela.

DPC: Month saw biggest anti-govt demonstrations in years as students took to streets across country; over dozen killed in clashes with security forces, scores injured; hundreds arrested, most subsequently released. Over 500 complaints of abuses by security services according to rights groups. Events threatening to further erode stability, human rights in already polarised nation. Demonstrations protesting violent crime, economic crisis began in San Cristobal city in SW state T?chira 2 Feb. Students backed by ?La salida? movement, comprising wing of opposition alliance Democratic Unity (MUD), 12 Feb staged march to HQ of chief prosecutor Luisa Ortega D?az to demand release of those jailed and protest food shortages, inflation, crime. Violence broke out between small group of demonstrators and armed civilian supporters of govt; 2 people died in initial clashes and third later, all shot in head. Over 300 reportedly detained over following week, 2 more killed; detainees reported beatings, torture, death threats, other abuses. Govt 16 Feb issued arrest warrant for Voluntad Popular (VP) party founder Leopoldo L?pez accusing him of instigating violence, claimed opposition seeking violent overthrow of President Maduro. L?pez 18 Feb turned himself in; called for protesters to stay in streets but remain non-violent; taken to military prison to await trial. As protests continued govt sent in riot squads accompanied by civilian gunmen; forces attacked protesters, destroyed and stole property. Govt 20 Feb sent troops to T?chira, threatened to declare state of emergency there (crisis watch).                           IC: 3 U.S. diplomats given 48 hours to leave country 17 Feb for alleged involvement in supposed conspiracy (crisis watch). US is concerned about internal crisis in Venezuela. US Secretary of State John Kerry says he is working with Colombia and other countries to form a mediation strategy for Venezuela's political crisis (http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-26392262).  But no additional reports of elevated tension with another country that could lead to conflict.
dpcnotes: biggest anti-govt demonstrations in years as students took to streets across country

notes: DPC: Despite announcement by President Maduro and other leading govt members that protest movement launched early Feb (which they term a ?coup?) has been defeated, protests continued: most barricades rebuilt, no sign of protesters? determination wavering. Continued clashes between protesters and pro-govt forces; since protest movement began 39 people have been killed and 2,041 placed in detention facilities, half still with probationary measures. Security forces deployed 17 March on Plaza Altamira in Caracas, but rapidly outnumbered by peaceful civilian protesters from surrounding neighbourhoods. Govt?s ?peace conference? and truth commission set up in Feb failed to incorporate radicals or moderates from opposition Democratic Unity (MUD) alliance. FMs from Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) visited Caracas 25-27 March, met with opposition groups as well as govt. Immediately after UNASUR?s 12 March decision to send mission, Maduro announced he would take ?drastic measures? to end protests; announcement followed by deployment of National Guard in Caracas, arrest of mayors of San Cristobal (T?chira) and San Diego (Valencia), stripping of parliamentary immunity for MUD legislator Maria Corina Machado with view to prosecuting her for murder of political violence victims, and arrest of 3 air force generals for alleged coup plot. Vatican 28 March announced it is willing to facilitate peaceful resolution of crisis; Maduro said govt would accept its mediation (crisis watch).
dpcnotes: Anti-gov protest

notes: DPC: Tensions remained high: opposition Democratic Unity (MUD) alliance coordinator 13 May said talks with govt "in crisis"; President Maduro 14 May said he had no intention of abandoning talks, hoped MUD would reciprocate. Regional FMs acting as negotiation facilitators visited, held meetings with both sides 18 May in bid to break deadlock but no progress made. Intensity of student-led protests continued to decline, but no easing of repression on part of security forces: 4 peace camps set up by protesters in different parts of Caracas violently dismantled 8 May (crisis watch). Arson attacks against a high street retail branch of state-owned Banco del Tesoro and a vehicle from national oil company PDVSA occurred on 19 May in Lecher?a, Diego Bautista Urbaneja municipality, in the eastern Anzotegui state. University students and civil society groups have been staging anti-government protests since 4 February, with 44 people - most of them protesters - killed, more than 750 injured, and thousands arrested (jane's intelligence weekly, May 20). A POLICE officer was shot and killed by an unidentified sniper as police attempted to clear anti-government protest camps in Venezuelas capital Caracas on 8 May, the BBC reported. Three other police officers were wounded during clashes with demonstrators and 243 protesters were detained during raids across the city (jane's).
dpcnotes: Anti-gov student-led protest

DPC: Furious residents of Ituni and Kwakwani continue to block the main access road into their community in protest of its deplorable state for the past 40 years. A huge log blocks vehicles from passing along the Kwakwani/Ituni road (opensource, Sep 2). As protestors vow to continue blocking the Kwakwani/Ituni access road due to its deplorable state for the past 40 years, 16 persons have been arrested (opensource, Sep 4). On the heels of the protest action that saw the blocking of the Kwakwani/Ituni access road, the Alliance For Change (AFC) is calling on the Government to heed the call of residents (opensource, Sep 7). Events do not seem widespread enough to be coded DPC.

Guayaquil El Universo on 6 September reports that fewer people took to the streets yesterday to protest the government?s decision to drill for oil in the Yasuni rainforest preserve then they did last week, the first Yasuni protest march after the decision was announced. While the first march gathered around 500 people according to the government and 1,000 people according to El Universo, the daily reports that yesterday evening?s march only comprised some 350 demonstrators (opensource, Sep 6). No additional reports. Event not widespread enough to be coded DPC.

notes: DPC: Local residents in Peru are staging an indefinite protest against mining company Minera Antamina to demand the relocation of a pipeline junction valve station and the construction of a hospital in Cajacay district, in Bolognesi province, in the country's northern Ancash department (jane's, Sep 5). The Peruvian government yesterday approved a national fund of nearly USD 283.6 million (PEN800 million) for regions at risk of the suspension of important local projects in the event of a decrease in mining contributions due to a global commodity price fall (jane's, Sep 9). A 24-hour strike staged by unions organised under the General Confederation of Peruvian Workers (Confederaci?n General de Trabajadores del Per?: CGTP) took place on 26 September. The largest demonstrations took place in the capital Lima and in the cities of Arequipa, Ayacucho, Cusco, Chimbote, and Chiclayo. Workers protested against incumbent president Ollanta Humala's economic policies, and in particular demanded the resignation of Minister of Economy Miguel Castilla and an increase in wages (jane's). notes: INS: Security forces 10 April arrested 28 people suspected of links to Shining Path militant group, issued 6 arrest warrants against Peruvians living abroad, in operation involving over 300 police and army personnel. Detainees include 2 attorneys representing jailed Shining Path leader and rebel groups political wing Movement for Amnesty and Fundamental Rights (MOVADEF). President Humalas cousin also detained (crisis watch).                                  DPC: reports of protest in previous months (jane's, crisis watch). Independence Day celebrations in Brazil were the focus of social protests nationwide, but with markedly smaller numbers and less disruption than during the June 2013 mass protests. The smaller scale of the 7 September protests confirms that the dynamism of the June protests has abated, although some activist groups remain committed to using peaceful protests as cover for civil disorder and property damage. On July 30, jane's reported: "Approximately 90 indigenous Mapuche land rights activists attacked a police station near the commune of Alto B?o B?o, located in the southeastern region of B?o B?o in Chile, according to the regional governor. Tensions between Chile's indigenous community and the state have been high since January, when the government deployed additional security personnel to Araucan?a following the death in an arson attack of two elderly farmers at the hands of suspected Mapuche activists. Those sensitivities have been exacerbated by the government's use of anti-terrorism legislation to deal with Mapuche dissent. "  On June 27, jane's reported: "Members of the Confederation of Copper workers (Confederaci?n de Trabajadores del Cobre: CTC) and several regional port workers unions joined hundreds of thousands of students on 26 June in a nationwide strike in demand of free universal higher education. Beyond the usual disruptions in the capital Santiago, where radical elements of the student movement mounted barricades and engaged in violent confrontations with state security forces, the nationwide strike led to a number of operational disruptions to both mining facilities and ports across the country". DPC: FORTY-THREE police officers were wounded during violent clashes with protesters ? armed with incendiary devices and stones ? in the Chilean capital Santiago on 11 September, Terra and the BBC reported. The demonstrations centred on the anniversary of the 1973 coup d'?tat led by General Augusto Pinochet, which led to 17 years of military rule (jane's). Protest also in Valparaiso and Valdivia (jane's, bbc). Incidents Take Place During Demonstration Organized by Confech in Downtown Santiago -- Santiago El Mercurio reports on 6 September that the Student Government Federation (Confech) held a new demonstration in downtown Santiago on 5 September. Several incidents were reported in Mercado Central, on Bandera Street, and in Estacion Mapocho.  According to the Confech, more than 80,000 people participated in the demonstration, while the Carabineros Police Force estimated that 25,000 people participated in the demonstration. A total 214 people were arrested during the demonstration (opensource).

AT LEAST one police officer was wounded during armed clashes which began after activists ? marking the Young Combatants Day ? erected barricades, fired shots, and engaged with security forces across Chile?s capital Santiago on 29 and 30 March, Latin American Herald Tribune reported. Police detained 92 people (jane's). SEVEN police officers were shot and wounded when ethnic Mapuche Indians activists ambushed them while they were escorting firefighters attempting to extinguish a fire set by the activists at a forestry company in an unspecified location in Chile?s Araucania region on 3 March, the Latin American Herald Tribune reported (jane's). Tens of thousands of Chileans have marched through Santiago to urge new President Michelle Bachelet to carry out her left-leaning reform programme. The key demand of the activists was that the Pinochet-era constitution be replaced with a document that protects the rights of all citizens. The student movement, which led much of the protests against the previous centre-right government, did not take part in the protest (http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-26703699).

See for example: " Student Organizations Postpone 24 April Demonstration -- Santiago La Tercera on 16 April carries a report by Juan Pablo Andrews stating that the Coordinating Assembly of High School Students of Chile (Aces), the National Coordinating Board of High School Students (Cones), and the Student Government Federation (Confech) issued a press release announcing that they had decided to postpone the student march they planned to hold on 24 April due to the 1 April earthquake and the fire that broke out in the city of Valparaiso on 12 April. The student organizations are now working to collect relief goods and are organizing volunteer work. The press release added that the organizations will set a new date taking into consideration progress made in the reconstruction processes. The press release points out that the student movement is playing a leading role in the relief work." (opensource, April 17). Opensource also reports that students plan a large demonstration in May.   Code 0 and check again next month.

DPC: Large-scale protests often involving hundreds of thousands of students have regularly caused disruption in the centre of the capital Santiago and, to a lesser extent, provincial cities such as Valparaiso. The intensity of these protests subsided during the general election campaign in late 2013 and the period leading up to the inauguration of President Michelle Bachelet in March 2014. Since then there has been one Federation of University of Chile Students (Federaci?n de Estudiantes de la Universidad de Chile: FECH) supported protest, on 8 May, which attracted between 30,000 and 100,000 protesters in Santiago, according to conflicting reports. The head of FECH, Melissa Sepulveda, claimed the student movement was unhappy with the proposals outlined in the government's bill and called for a protest against the proposed legislation in Valparaiso on 21 May (jane's intelligence weekly, May 20). AT LEAST 20 police officers were wounded during violent protests by students demanding free education across Chile on 8 May, Latin American Herald Tribune reported. Three officers were reportedly wounded by incendiary devices. A police spokesman stated that 101 people were arrested during the demonstrations (jane's). Smooth back in April DPC in Chile.

Police used rubber bullets and tear gas to try and control protestors who threw rocks. A total of 6 police officers and 20 protestors were injured. The official opening of campaigning for Argentina's 27 October mid-term legislative elections began on 22 September, with leading opposition candidate Sergio Massa coming under attack from government supporters in greater Buenos Aires. DPC: Argentine truck drivers protested in Buenos Aires on 10 March causing transport chaos and business disruption in the country's capital (jane's). A leader of the Truck Drivers' Union (Sindicator de Choferes de Camiones: SICHOCA), Pablo Moyano, stated on 13 March 2014 the union would renew blockades to steel manufacturing firm Siderar's operations from next week and would not take part in the obligatory negotiations ordered by the Ministry of Labour (jane's). Protesters from neighbourhood social movements on 19 March brought serious disruption to transit and business in central Buenos Aires, cutting the key Avenida 9 de Julio in support of their demands that the city government increase spending in poor semi-formal housing areas of the Argentine capital. The demonstration came only a few days after port workers participating in a "piquetero" (picket) protest over union disputes on 12 March blocked the Avellaneda bridge connecting the suburb of Avellaneda with the Buenos Aires La Boca district, leading to a confrontation that resulted in one seriously injured bystander. On 25 February, several thousand piquetero activists blocked the central 9 de Julio Avenue in the capital during a demonstration against government social policy, with several of the groups announcing major protests in the following weeks (jane's). See also: http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-26542445.   Check again next month.                      IC: no reports of tension with another country (jane's, crisis watch, bbc, guardian).

notes: DPC: Argentine media reports said the 10 April national strike, carried out by the country's main labour union confederations (Confederaci?n General del Trabajo de la Rep?blica Argentina: CGT, and Central de Trabajadores Argentinos: CTA) cost USD1.3 billion in losses. The strike effectively stopped the country's ports, airports, Buenos Aires city metro, and the bus service. Several large unions allied with the government did not take part; however, the ability of the strikers to bring transportation to a halt proved highly disruptive (jane's intelligence weekly, April 15, http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-26984031). An estimated 10,000 activists gathered at Buenos Aires' Central Market to listen to a number of key figures within President Cristina Fern?ndez de Kirchner's Victory Front (Frente para la Victoria: FpV) appeal for unity within 'Kirchnerism' (jane's). notes: DPC: anti-gov protest in many cities across Spain: ELEVEN people were wounded ?including five police officers - and 11 were arrested during violent protests in Spain?s capital Madrid late on 15 January, Reuters reported. The protest was one of 46 across cities in Spain against a state-financed project in the northern city of Burgos to convert a street into a tree-lined boulevard and build a new carpark that the public must pay for (jane's). According to Jane's Intelligence weekly, protest began in Nov and will probably intensify in the following months: "The protests, which began in November 2013, serve as an indicator for the rising potential for civil disorder, both violent and peaceful, across Spain. The Gamonal dispute reflected local discontent over a project that would have pedestrianised a major commercial street, replacing free parking with a fee-paying underground car park. The project was seen by residents as benefiting two local construction firms close to the People's Party (Partido Popular: PP) municipal administration while hurting local businesses. However, it also showed more generalised anger over public sector cuts and spending priorities, along with the deterioration of business conditions in the area. The Gamonal riots illustrate how a long-standing local issue, that concerned only those living or having businesses in Gamonal, was able to attract support from activists, including those on the left, initially in Burgos and then from across Spain. Although local protests initially were peaceful, the later demonstrations resulted in riots and violent confrontations with police. This included several nights of disturbances in late January 2014 and around EUR50,000 of damage to property, mainly bank offices and refuse containers. Furthermore, the protests spread to several other cities with limited localised violence, and solidarity rallies were held across Spain (including significant protests in Pamplona, Vigo, Valladolid, Zaragoza, Valencia, Alicante, and Oviedo). In Madrid, 15 arrests were made on 15 January after part of a 500-strong demonstration attempted to attack the ruling PP's national headquarters in solidarity with the Gamonal protesters." (jane's, Feb 6)
dpcnotes: anti-gov protest (Gamonal dispute) spreaded to many cities across Spain.

Around 3,500 protestors demonstrated peacefully in Alc?zar de San Juan (Ciudad Real) on 21 February, following a sit-in at the local town hall over the previous three days. The rolling work stoppages and associated demonstrations will affect all economic sectors and severely disrupt public transport. DPC: Janes': "Small but disruptive protests by the "pitchfork" (Forconi) movement across Italy. Demonstrations by farmers, truck drivers, students, and anti-government protesters representing a variety of different economic grievances carry a high risk of violent confrontation with police and property damage to commercial assets, banks, and government buildings. A protest in Rome is unlikely to be larger than a few tens of thousands of people. However, it is likely to attract far-right and anarchist groups keen to exploit the protests to engage in fighting with the police. Protests carry a high risk of business disruption, violent confrontation with police and property damage to commercial assets, banks, and government buildings. No date has been set for a planned march in Rome next week. Although the Rome rally is unlikely to be larger than a few tens of thousands of people, it will also attract small numbers of far-right, Ultra (football hooligan) groups and anarchists keen to exploit protests to engage in fighting with police. Temporary road blockades and occupation of public buildings by Forconi protesters are likely, but police have the capacity to ensure such incidents are shortlived and localised. The spillover of economic frustration and anger raises the risk of more violent and disruptive protests in 2014."

notes: DPC: Anti-austerity demonstrators and "black bloc" anarchists attempted to lay siege to Italy's Ministry of Social Affairs and Employment in central Rome on 12 April.  An array of disparate left-wing social interest groups rallied in central Rome over the weekend of 12/13 April. Ostensibly protests were over social housing policies and legislation denying squatters' access to public services. The demonstration was also joined by protesters against the planned "Jobs Act" simplifying the country's labour market. According to Rome's Chief of Police, Alessandro Pansa, riot police launched "pre-emptive" baton charges and fired tear gas to clear the streets. Footage released on 15 April appears to show the police employing heavy-handed tactics which is likely to sway public opinion in favour of the demonstrators and is likely to bring more activists onto the street at future anti-austerity rallies. The majority of Labour Day protests scheduled throughout Italy on 1 May are likely to pass off peacefully. However, there is an increased risk of commercial property damage in city centre districts, mainly concentrated in Milan, Rome, and Turin. Protest leaders are highly likely to mobilise for the 10-11 July summit of EU leaders in Turin, after Italy assumes the six month rotating presidency of the European Union (jane's intelligence weekly, April 15).           Check again next month.

DPC: Protests began in over 30 towns early Feb, triggered by collapse of privatised companies in Tuzla and resulting layoffs. Hundreds of redundant workers gathered in front of govt building in Tuzla 5 Feb calling for compensation; over 30 injured, 27 arrested. Several thousand joined protests 6 Feb, scores injured; protests began in Sarajevo and other places same day in support of Tuzla protesters and over economic conditions; 8 Feb spread to 32 towns in Bosniak-Croat entity, with protesters in some cities attacking and setting fire to govt buildings, clashing with police; several hundred injured, scores detained. Several politicians resigned, including canton govts in Tuzla and Zenica. Situation calmed 9 Feb, though protests continued demanding further resignations, measures to curb corruption, improve economy. Small protest also in Republika Srpska capital. Governing Social Democratic Party 12 Feb submitted proposal to parliament to change state-level electoral law to enable early elections. Sarajevo canton govt late Feb accepted protesters? demands for govt of experts, lower wages for officials (crisis watch). Reports also in jane's.

notes: DPC: Almost 4,000 protesters attend Bucharest rally against Rosia Montana gold mining project (opensource, Oct 14).Villagers protest Chevron's shale gas explorations in Pungesti (opensource, Oct 17). Approximately 800 protesters demonstrated on 19 October in the Pungesti commune, Vaslui County, in Romania's northeastern region against shale gas exploration, according to Reuters news agency. The demonstration was non-violent and involved environmentalists and locals. DPC: Jane's: Mass protests in southern Russia's Saratov region indicate growing unrest in civil society: on the evening of 8 July several hundred local residents attempted to start a mass fight with internal migrants from the North Caucasus who have settled in Pugachev. In addition to the mass demonstration on 9 July, during which about 1,000 local residents demanded the resettlement of migrants from the North Caucasus, several hundred protesters attempted to storm the county administrative buildings and to block the Samara-Volgograd highway. During the night of 8 July attempts were made to set fire to a caf? where North Caucasus immigrants frequently meet, according to local media reports. Large numbers of police personnel and special armoured police units were at the scene; armoured police were not actively deployed. The protests are ongoing and will likely continue in coming days.
rebnotes: No evidence for a cessation of rebellious activity in southern regions of Chechnya and Dagestan

REB: Regional and municipal elections 8 Sept saw local parliaments elect republic heads (presidents) in Dagestan (Ramazan Abdulatipov) and Ingushetia (Yunus-Bek Yevkurov) from candidates proposed by Kremlin. Ruling ?United Russia? won Chechen parliamentary elections with 85.94% of vote. Caucasian Knot reported 42 people killed in conflict in Aug. Increasingly harsh counter-terrorism operations, rhetoric ahead of Feb 2014 Sochi Winter Olympics; Yevkurov announced homes of families helping insurgents will be demolished, land seized; Putin 27 Sept introduced legislation for compensation for losses caused by terrorism at expense of terrorists? relatives, and creation of mechanism for reviewing legality of property acquired by terrorists? relatives and friends. Major insurgency attacks during month included: 3 police killed in suicide bomb attack 16 Sept in Sunzhensky district police station, Chechnya; double terrorist attack in Ingushetia same day, 1 killed. Investigators suspect group led by Beslan Makhauri on Chechnya-Ingushetia border; counter-terrorism operation (CTO) regime introduced in Sunzhensky. 2 police killed, 15 injured by suicide bomber in Tabasaransky district police station, Dagestan 23 Sept. Dagestan Supreme Court judge Mukhtar Shapiyev shot dead with son 25 Sept. Govt operations included CTO killing leader of Kabardino-Balkaria?s ?Urvan? insurgency group Ruslan Makoev and 2 accomplices in Urvansky district, KBR 5 Sept. Dagestani authorities reported leader of Kadar insurgency Tagir Sulabanov, father and associate killed in clash with police 24 Sept. Security forces continued pressure on Salafi communities in Dagestan, including harassment of Salafi rights organisation ?Pravozaschita?. Religious activist Abdul Gappaev shot dead in Kizlyar, Dagestan 15 Sept (crisis watch).                       IC: Russian deputy foreign minister Sergei Ryabkov announced on 18 September that the Syrian government had furnished further evidence that a chemical attack had been executed by rebels in Syria (jane's). notes: DPC: Killing of ethnic Russian by North Caucasian in Biryulovo district, Moscow, sparked tensions between Russian nationalists and Caucasian, Central Asian immigrants, riots in Moscow 13 Oct (crisis watch). The Biryulevo riot was by no means the first recent example of Russian nationalist violence towards migrants, although it was significant for its scale and unexpected escalation. The Moscow police had to activate their emergency mobilisation plan 'Volcano' and recall off-duty officers, and detain around 400 rioters and more than 1,600 alleged illegal migrants in subsequent sweeps. During the riot, a shopping centre and one of the country's largest vegetable warehouses were damaged as both were perceived to employ large numbers of migrant workers. In the days following the unrest, Russian media also reported attacks on several people from Central Asia and the Caucasus (jane's). I coded DPC 1, becuase riots are not explicitly connected to the rebellion in the south Caucasus.                                   REB: Female suicide bomber from Dagestan 21 Oct targeted bus in southern Russian city Volgograd, killing 6 and injuring 55, in country?s first terrorist attack outside N Caucasus since 2011. Director of Federal Security Service and head of National Anti-terrorist Committee Alexander Bortnikov 8 Oct declared progress in fight against terrorism; cited decrease in number of terrorist attacks this year (144 attacks) compared with 2012 (270 attacks); most attacks in Dagestan. Also mentioned threats to Feb 2014 Sochi Winter Olympics from militants from Syria and Afghanistan-Pakistan, reiterated commitment to increasing security in run-up. Major security incidents included: 4 insurgents, 3 police and 3 militia members killed in Levashinsky district, Dagestan 2 Oct; 2 suspected suicide bombers killed in failed attack after devices detonated early 18 Oct in Dygulubgey village, Kabardino-Balkaria; series of attacks on police officers in Dagestan, 2 killed 9 Oct; 1 killed, 15 injured in double bombing near shop selling alcohol in Makhachkala 30 Oct. Aznaur Khizriev, leader of local terrorist group in Khasavyurt, Dagestan, killed in shoot-out 12 Oct. Continued pressure on Salafi community in Dagestan: police raids in Leninkent village mosque and on halal cafes in Makhachkala; security services closed Muslim kindergarten in Makhachkala and women?s madrasa in Novosasitli (crisis watch).
dpcnotes: Anti-immigrants riots in Moscow

Security forces began anti-terrorist trainings ahead of Sochi Olympics. Increase in CTOs in Dagestan; almost daily security incidents: 3 militants killed in Makhachkala 27 Nov; 2 militants and 2 women killed during special operation in Novosasitli, Khasavyurt district 20 Nov; 2 police killed in Kumtorkalinsky district 14 Nov; 1 killed in terrorist attack on department store in Makhachkala 8 Nov; 3 militants including Levashinsky insurgent group leader killed 4 Nov during operation in Laksky district; In Kabardino-Balkaria 4 suspected militants killed in Baksan district 18, 20 Nov. Leader of Plievskaya insurgent group and another militant killed in Ingushetia 27 Nov. Sustained pressure on Salafi communities in Dagestan: 40 Salafis detained in Makhachkala 14 Nov; 6 injured in 15 Nov brawl when Salafis were denied entrance to mosque in Leninkent near Makhachkala. Tensions rose over land disputes: ethnic Kumyks protested after 11 Nov detention of 15 activists in Karaman, Dagestan; following long-term conflict with republican authorities ethnic Balkars took over distribution of land in Beleya Rechka village 18-19 Nov. Justice official Zainutdin Madanov gunned down 4 Nov in Makhachkala; fourth judge killed in N Caucasus this year (crisis watch). U.S. to move 2 warships into Black Sea. Caucasus Emirate, Islamist insurgency organisation, declared expansion of their ?state? to Sochi and Krasnodar Kray and creation of ?Vilayat Cherkessia?. Caucasian Knot website reported 986 victims of NC insurgency in 2013, including 529 killed; also 187 victims of 3 suicide bombings in Volgograd, 44 killed. Highest number of victims in Dagestan (641), then Kabardino-Balkaria, Chechnya. Insurgent group Vilayat Dagestan 20 Jan claimed responsibility for Dec Volgograd bombings in which 34 people killed, threatened to strike Olympics; National Anti-terrorist Committee blames Dagestan?s Buynaksk insurgency. 6 civilians found shot dead in 4 vehicles in Stavropol Kray, southern Russia 8/9 Jan; 4 vehicles booby-trapped, CTO regime introduced in 2 districts, 3 Kabardino-Balkaria residents suspected in killings. Over a dozen suspected militants killed in special operations and clashes with security forces in Dagestan including militant leader Makhmud Aliyev and suspected female suicide bomber 18 Jan. 4 suspected militants, 3 police killed in special operation in Khasavyurt district 15 Jan. 16 people injured by bomb in Makhachkala 17 Jan. Chechen President Kadyrov 16 Jan reported evidence that Caucasus Emirate leader Doku Umarov is dead; also made tough statements against ?Wahhabis?, followed by wave of detentions and searches of men with beards and women in hijabs (crisis watch).

notes: DPC: Several human rights, environmental and Circassian protesters detained during Olympics including 37 Circassian activists for 7 Feb demonstration against Olympics in Kabardino-Balkaria capital Nalchik (crisis watch). Police in Moscow detained 420 political demonstrators on 24 February in an operation in which the number of security personnel greatly exceeded the number of protesters. The demonstrators were protesting against what they perceived to be unfair sentences issued by a Moscow court on 24 February to political activists who used force against police during mass anti-government protests in central Moscow on 6 May 2012. The first activists to be sentenced in the so-called Bolotnaya Square case received prison sentences of between two and a half years and four years; state prosecutors asked the judge for a sentence of 5-6 years. Around 1,000 demonstrators gathered outside the court building in the morning and then in Manezh Square, next to the Kremlin, in the afternoon. Alongside the heavy police presence, Red Square, Manezh Square, and several streets in central Moscow were also shut down (jane's intelligence weekly). Protest not widespread enough to be coded DPC.                     REB: Security forces 5 Feb killed alleged organiser of Volgograd bombings Dzhamaldin Mirzayev in Izberbash, Dagestan. Kabardino-Balkaria Islamic insurgent leader Tengiz Guketlov 9 Feb claimed responsibility for Jan murder of 6 civilians in Stavropol, said they were in retaliation for 35 civilian deaths by security forces. Over 10 suspected militants killed during special security operations including 5 Buynaksk militants in Makhachkala 8 Feb; 3 militants killed in Khasavyurt District, Dagestan 12 Feb. Security services blew up house of relatives of killed insurgent during special operation in Novy Agachaul village, Dagestan 20 Feb (crisis watch). Reports also in jane's.                  IC: Tension with Ukraine due to pro-Europe protests in Ukraine in Feb. Russian mobilization aganist Ukraine started March 1 (all sources. ).

notes: REB: Insurgency news website Kavkaz Center 18 March reported Caucasus Emirate leader and Russia?s most wanted terrorist Doku Umarov dead, apparently confirming rumours circulating since Jan, said Emirate?s Sharia judge Dagestani Ali Abu Mohammed (Aliaskhab Kebekov) selected as his replacement; National Anti-terrorist Committee has not confirmed Umarov?s death. In Dagestan at least 4 suspected militants, 1 suspected of involvement in Dec 2013 Volgograd attacks, killed in special operation in Izberbash 3 March. 2 police injured by militant shelling in Dagestan capital Makhachkala 17 March. Several members of illegal armed formations, 1 security agent killed 25 March during special operation in Khasavyurt district. Several suspected militants killed in counter-terrorism operation in Nalchik, Kabardino-Balkaria 14 March. 2 suspected militants killed in special operation in Ingushetia 22 March. NC republics demonstrated support for Russia?s Crimea invasion: Dagestan, Ingushetia, N Ossetia, Chechnya saw mass solidarity demonstrations, people reportedly forced to participate in some cases; republics sent aid (crisis watch).                                IC: Russia annexed Crimea in move condemned as illegal by Western states, fuelling uncertainty in region, fears of war between Russia and Ukraine. Russian legislature 1 March approved use of armed forces in Ukraine to protect ethnic Russians, Russian armed forces in Crimea. Crimean parliament 6 March voted in favour of joining Russia, scheduled 16 March referendum: authorities claimed 97% yes vote, parliament next day applied to join Russia. Russian President Putin and pro-Russian leaders in Crimea 18 March signed treaties making Crimea part of Russia; pro-Russian forces seized Ukrainian military installations, captured several military officers. Second half of month saw heavy Russian troop build-up on Ukrainian border, prompting expressions of concern from U.S., NATO. Putin 21 March signed laws formalising Russian annexation of Crimea, ordered Russian govt administration to be installed by 29 March. Acting Ukrainian President Turchynov ordered withdrawal of all Ukrainian troops from Crimea. U.S., EU refused to recognise referendum, imposed targeted sanctions on senior Russian officials, private individuals and bank with close ties to govt; offered financial aid to Kiev. G8 members meeting without Russia 25 March suspended Russian membership, cancelled upcoming G8 meeting in Sochi. U.S. Sec State Kerry and Russian FM Lavrov met for talks 30 March, no breakthrough (crisis watch).
rebnotes: Rebellion in North Caucasus continued.
icnotes: Russia annexed Crimea in move condemned as illegal by Western states

Caucasus Knot reported 133 killed or injured in NC conflict in first quarter of 2014, mostly in Dagestan. In Dagestan, attacks included: Imam shot dead by 2 unknown gunmen in Kizil-Yurt district; security forces killed several suspected militants during operation in Makhachkala 15 April; lawmaker shot dead by unknown assailants 17 April; 6 militants, including woman, killed in Derabent 26 April; 4 militants killed in Khasavyurt 24 April. In Chechnya, 4 police killed in mine explosion 3 April. 2 suspected militants killed in Stepnovsky district, Stavropol Krai 28 April. Some 400 Ingush attended protest rallies over illegal detentions in Prigorodny district, North Ossetia 10-11 April; rallies saw clashes with police, several detained (crisis watch). reports also in jane's.                              IC: Pro-Russian separatists in Ukraine seized control of over a dozen towns and cities in east leading to deadly clashes with Ukrainian troops as Kyiv struggled unsuccessfully to reassert control, continuing fears of Russian intervention and tensions between Russia and West. Pro-Russian gunmen 12 April began taking control of state buildings in cities in east; Moscow denied allegations of Russian forces? involvement. U.S., Russia, EU and Ukraine 17 April reached agreement at talks in Geneva on steps to de-escalate crisis; accord quickly broke down after separatists occupying govt buildings refused to leave, seized OSCE military observers, journalists, security personnel in Sloviansk and govt buildings elsewhere in SE. Russia accused Kyiv of breaking terms of agreement; U.S. and EU blamed Russia, introduced new sanctions on Russian individuals and companies. NATO 16 April announced it was strengthening eastern members? defences. Russian defence minister Shoigu said no plans to invade Ukraine or intervene in SE Ukraine along lines of Crimea (crisis watch). reports also in jane's.

DPC: Crisis as pro-Europe Euromaidan protests escalated, govt crackdown resulted in deadly clashes between protesters and police and growing political confrontation with opposition. Parliament 16 Jan passed draconian new anti-protest laws, also amended Criminal Code restricting free speech; law criticised by opposition as illegal, condemned internationally. Hundreds of protesters clashed with police 19 Jan; 2 protesters shot dead in clashes with police 22 Jan, third died later from injuries; another protester found dead bearing signs of torture. Dozens of demonstrators arrested, jailed since protests started, several missing. President Yanukovych 20 Jan called for dialogue, in talks with opposition offered truce if protesters refrained from violence, remove barricades; opposition rejected offer, called for snap presidential elections, changes to constitution. Protesters seized govt offices in Kiev and several other cities including in east. Govt resigned 28 Jan in attempt to resolve crisis, parliament same day overturned 16 Jan anti-protest law. Parliament 29 Jan passed amnesty law for protesters; opposition rejected condition of amnesty that protesters vacate occupied govt buildings, continued to call for Yanukovych?s resignation. EU foreign policy chief Ashton visited 29 Jan for talks with Yanukovych; Russia 29 Jan said it would defer fulfilment of $15bn aid package to Ukraine until new govt formed. Amid international condemnation of violence and calls for dialogue, concerns also voiced over disunity within opposition, lack of strategy, role of extreme right element (crisis watch).
dpcnotes: Anti-gov protest.

notes: INS: no reports of events (jane's). All reports seem related to DPC.               DPC: Scores killed as anti-govt protesters clashed with police in worst violence since independence; following opposition ouster of President Yanukovych new interim govt confronted by grave concerns over weak central authority, economic crisis, role of nationalist and rightist elements in new govt; mounting threat of separatism in east as unrest broke out in majority ethnic Russian Crimea, West warned Russia against intervention. Anti-govt protesters vacated Kiev City Hall 16 Feb after govt released all 234 jailed protesters, but clashes broke out between protesters and police 18 Feb after protesters marched to parliament demanding progress on constitutional reform to reduce presidential powers; at least 26 killed including 10 police. Govt and opposition announced truce 19 Feb, but renewed clashes broke out 20 Feb; dozens killed, hundreds injured, many reportedly from gunshot wounds. Health ministry reported 83 killed in political violence since 18 Feb. EU, U.S. responded with targeted sanctions. Yanukovych and opposition 21 Feb agreed to form new govt, hold new election under EU-mediated deal; parliament voted to release former PM Yulia Tymoshenko from jail, restore 2004 constitution. Yanukovych 22 Feb fled capital; parliament same day voted to remove president, hold early presidential election 25 May; 23 Feb elected opposition leader Olexander Turchynov interim president (crisis watch).                     IC: tension with Russia. Yanukovych called events coup, backed by Russia which granted him protection. Russia suspended financial assistance, recalled ambassador; EU, U.S. said ready to provide financial assistance. In autonomous Crimea region pro-govt ethnic Russians and anti-govt ethnic Ukrainians and Muslim Tatars staged rival rallies late month. Anti-Russia protesters stormed parliament in regional capital Simferopol 26 Feb; well-armed and equipped troops calling themselves pro-Russian self-defence militia reportedly took over govt buildings, airport next day. Kiev 28 Feb said Russian forces occupying Crimea?s Sevastopol airport in ?armed invasion?. Russia claims these are also local self-defence groups; Russian official media claim similar armed groups protecting Perekop isthmus connecting Crimea to Ukrainian mainland. Crimean govt announced it had taken control of all security forces on peninsula, pro-Russian Crimean PM 1 March appealed to Russia for help ensuring security; Kremlin said would not ignore call. U.S. and Western powers warned Russia against military intervention in Ukraine (crisis watch).

icnotes: Hightended Tension with Russia

notes: DPC: widespread unrest through most of month as pro-Russian protesters in SE demonstrated against Kiev govt, often demanding to join Russia (crisis watch). On 25 March security services killed Oleksandr Muzychko, head of the ultranationalist militant organisation Pravyi Sektor's western Ukraine network. Police also arrested the head of Pravyi Sektor's eastern Ukraine network. The government is attempting to re-establish control over Ukraine's internal security. Notably, Pravyi Sektor and other ultranationalist militant groups, which were at the forefront of the December 2013 - February 2014 anti-government protests, have refused to comply with the government's request to surrender all unregistered weapons on 21 March (jane's). The Ukrainian riot police block the entrance of the regional administrative building during a pro-Russian protest in Donetsk, Ukraine, on 9 March. In eastern provinces, pro-Russian demonstrations persisted, as the provincial administration headquarters in Donetsk changed hands between protesters and police.1530841The Ukrainian riot police block the entrance of the regional administrative building during a pro-Russian protest in Donetsk, Ukraine, on 9 March. In eastern provinces, pro-Russian demonstrations persisted, as the provincial administration headquarters in Donetsk changed hands between protesters and police (jane's). Additional reports of protests in jane's.                            IC:  Russia annexed Crimea in move condemned as illegal by Western states, fuelling uncertainty in region, fears of war between Russia and Ukraine. Russian legislature 1 March approved use of armed forces in Ukraine to protect ethnic Russians, Russian armed forces in Crimea. Crimean parliament 6 March voted in favour of joining Russia, scheduled 16 March referendum: authorities claimed 97% yes vote, parliament next day applied to join Russia. Russian President Putin and pro-Russian leaders in Crimea 18 March signed treaties making Crimea part of Russia; pro-Russian forces seized Ukrainian military installations, captured several military officers. Second half of month saw heavy Russian troop build-up on Ukrainian border, prompting expressions of concern from U.S., NATO. Putin 21 March signed laws formalising Russian annexation of Crimea, ordered Russian govt administration to be installed by 29 March. Acting Ukrainian President Turchynov ordered withdrawal of all Ukrainian troops from Crimea. U.S., EU refused to recognise referendum, imposed targeted sanctions on senior Russian officials, private individuals and bank with close ties to govt; offered financial aid to Kiev. G8 members meeting without Russia 25 March suspended Russian membership, cancelled upcoming G8 meeting in Sochi. U.S. Sec State Kerry and Russian FM Lavrov met for talks 30 March, no breakthrough (crisis watch).
dpcnotes: pro-Russian protesters in SE demonstrated against Kiev govt
icnotes: Russia annexed Crimea in move condemned as illegal by Western states

notes: We should recode the events in Ukraine as REB and not DPC starting April 2014. Since April, attacks by separatists in east are much more organized and violent (no more protest).                              INS: events are related to REB (see below).                       DPC: events are related to REB (see below).                           REB: Presidential elections held 25 May: businessman Petro O. Poroshenko elected by wide margin, vowed to end war, unite Ukraine and push for early parliamentary elections in 2014. Violence continued in east where pro-Russian separatists prevented voting in Donetsk and Luhansk regions. Russian President Putin 7 May called for postponement of independence referendums in east to encourage dialogue, said presidential elections move in right direction; referendums nevertheless held 11 May in Donetsk and Luhansk regions; separatists announced 90% voted in favour of peoples republics amid claims of widespread voter fraud. Acting president Turchynov 1 May reinstated conscription, warned Ukraine on full combat alert. 2 Ukrainian military helicopters shot down 2 May by separatists, pilot and serviceman killed; around 42 killed in clashes in Odessa same day. About 20 killed in Mariupol clashes 9 May. Major battle for control of Donetsk airport 27 May, at least 30 separatists reported killed. Ukrainian general among 14 reported killed when helicopter downed near Slovyansk 29 May. 4 OSCE military observers reported missing in Donetsk region 26 May; at least 16 soldiers killed by separatists at checkpoint near Donetsk 22 May (crisis watch). Since 2 May, more than 100 people have died in fighting between Ukraine's security forces, nationalist demonstrators, and pro-Russian separatists (jane's). Separatist referenda were held in Ukraine's eastern Donetsk and Luhansk regions on 11 May, with the organisers claiming that an overwhelming majority of participants voted in favour of self-rule for the regions (jane's). Two separate ambushes by pro-Russian separatists in Ukraine's eastern province of Donetsk on 13 May killed at least 15 members of the security services and destroyed several armoured vehicles (jane's). The Central Election Commission on 22 May announced that 18 of 34 polling locations in Donetsk and Luhansk provinces were blocked by separatists (jane's).                                   IC: crisis with Russia continued. UNSC 28 May discussed Ukraine, UN political chief Jeffrey Feltman said violence in east dramatically escalated; at early May meeting Russia warned of catastrophic consequences of Kyiv military operations, U.S. said response proportionate and reasonable. NATO Sec Gen Rasmussen 30 May said signs of partial withdrawal of Russian troops from near Ukrainian border (crisis watch).
rebnotes: Many Attacks by eastern separatists.
icnotes: Crisis with Russia.

notes: DPC: CrisisWatch and Janes': "Opposition sit-ins and protests around the 21 December election being violently dispersed by security forces. The opposition Coordination of the Democratic Opposition (COD) called on its supporters to boycott the 21 December runoff parliamentary and local elections. The Islamist Tawassol party, the only member of the 11-party COD to take part in the first round, claimed the poll was marred by fraud. Voter turnout is likely to be low in the second round, with opposition protests consisting of thousands of demonstrators likely in Nouakchott and Nouadhibou and major urban centres such as Atar, Zoueratem Rosso and Kaedi. Security forces are likely to aggressively disperse protesters and any sympathetic impromptu strikes using anti-riot weapons."

DPC: Article about Prophet Muhammad Provokes Uproar: In the recent days tens of demonstrations were organized in several Mauritanian cities to protest against a controversial article posted in a local news website deemed critical of Islam's prophet Muhammad (opensource, Jan 6). Thousands of demonstrators, in the city of Nouadhibou, managed on 8 January morning, to break into the justice palace to protest the failure of judicial authorities in the city to prosecute the author of the article that offended Prophet Muhammad, peace be upon him, the messenger of Allah (opensource). Demonstration to Denounce Facebook Post: On January 10, thousands of Nouakchott inhabitants demonstrated in front of the Presidency to demand the death penalty for twenty eight year old Mohamed Ould Cheikh Ould MKheytir who recently posted an article on Facebook deemed critical of the Prophet Muhammad (opensource). Mauritanian workers continue to demonstrate unjust working conditions at the Tasiast mines (opensource, Jan 27).

notes: INS: no reports of insurgency-realted events (crisis watch, jane's)                               DPC: demonstrations against the desecration of the Koran continued (jane's). Public anger has been compounded by two recent incidents of alleged blasphemy: In February, a man was arrested and sent for psychiatric evaluation after urinating on a Koran in northern Mauritania. A young Muslim is facing a possible death sentence after being convicted in January of apostasy and jailed for writing an article criticising the Prophet Mohammed (http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-26423285). Mauritania's 25 February movement issues a press release describing police repression and arrests at their recent anti-government protest (opensource, Feb 6). Several areas in the capital Nouakchott witnessed today, Sunday [16 February], a state of lack of security during which several schools in Nouakchott were attacked by numerous groups calling themselves the `Prophet's supporters'. The storming of these schools by the groups had caused injuries among the students. According to eyewitnesses, the groups targeted the schools in order to get the students out to participate in protests they were organising. They used stones and sticks in their attacks on the educational institutions which locked their doors tightly and prevented the groups from getting through (opensource, Feb 16).   This morning, the Mauritanian gendarmerie deployed some of its elements to face the protest march carried out by school students in the District of Dar Naim, in Nouakchott, against the failure of the legal authorities to prosecute the author of the offending article against the Prophet, peace be upon him. The school students managed to raise barricades on some roads, burn tires and disrupt traffic. In the same context, a unit of the National Guard dispersed this morning a protest in front of the prime minister's office, in the center of Nouakchott. Protesters were demanded the execution of Mohammed Sheikh Ould Mkheitir, the author of the article that offended the Prophet, Mohamed, peace be upon him (opensource, Feb 18).
