notes: DPC: Preparations for legislative elections scheduled 24 Sept continued; official campaigning began 24 Aug, main opposition parties participating. Opposition 23 Aug met with international partners in efforts to find consensus on electoral rolls. Opposition leaders Cellou Dalein Diallo and Sidya Tour? 22 and 27 Aug said preparations not satisfactory, behind schedule; Tour? threatened to resume peaceful protests (crisis watch). According to Guinean media on 4 August, President Alpha Cond? has accused the opposition of manipulating, financing, and drugging youths in order to foment anti-government unrest in Conakry, the country's capital, and "to discourage investors from coming to Guinea". The accusation levelled at the opposition came after three days of violent protests against frequent power outages in Conakry (jane's, Aug 7). Guinea has agreed a deal to buy in emergency power supplies in order to halt lengthy power blackouts that have led to angry demonstrations, particularly in the capital Conakry. During three days of violent protests last week, the four-storey headquarters of EDG in Conakry was ransacked and set on fire (jane's, Aug 9).  On 17 August, a week before the start of the official campaign period, a group of youths reportedly set fire to the house of the brother of former prime minister Lansana Kouyate, leader of the Party of Hope for National Development  (jane's, Aug 19). The Guinean parliament opened on 13 January with the participation of the main opposition parties, which had been contesting some of the results of the 28 September 2013 parliamentary poll. Feb 2014: UNHCR 21 Feb reported almost 20,000 CAR refugees crossed into Cameroon in Feb. Jan 2014: 120 additional police deployed to border region following 31 Dec attack on Ondikiby by CAR militants. Military police confirmed Cameroonian forces 15 Jan repelled Nigerian Boko Haram fighters who tried to cross border; 5 killed (crisis watch).                   Dec 2013: Nigerian Islamist Sect Boko Haram (BH) 14 Dec attacked Kousseri town, leaving 2 dead; far-north governor imposed curfew in border areas, especially Mayo Sava, Mayo Tsanaga, Logone and Chari subdistricts. Armed groups from CAR 5 Dec perpetrated separate attacks in Ondiki and Bombe-Bakary, injuring 3 Rapid Intervention Battalion soldiers. Govt 18 Dec deployed troops to reinforce MISCA in CAR. Nigerian military 20 Dec confirmed army barracks attacked by BH in Bama, Borno came from cells located across border in Cameroon. Violence across border into Cameroon: Two rockets fired from Central African Republic landed in Garou-Mboulai border town in eastern province in Cameroon on 20 January. The strike caused property damage but no one was hurt. In retaliation the Cameroonian army shot dead two Central African rebels in the border area, one ex-Seleka and the other anti-Balaka, according to Defence minister Edgar Alain Mebe Ngo'o. On 12 January, a Cameroonian truck driver was killed in anti-Balaka/ex-Seleka crossfire 10 kilometres (km) from Garou-Mboulai inside CAR. According to Cameroonian media, ex-Seleka forces targeted the rockets at anti-Balaka units in Cantonnier, CAR, 1 km from the Cameroonian border. However, the devices overshot and landed in the Zougoud? neighbourhood of Garou-Mboulai (jane's, Jan 23).

THE Oromo Liberation Front (OLF) issued a statement on 18 May calling upon all forces that work for democracy, justice and freedom in Ethiopia to denounce the massacre of Oromo students by the minority dictatorial regime in Ethiopia, the BBC reported (jane's). DPC: Opensource.gov: "Tension Rises In Mozambique As Talks With Former Rebels Flounder" - 9/3/2013    The southern African country is organizing the poll, but the ex-rebel Mozambique National Resistance (Renamo) is demanding electoral reforms and changes to the electoral body. Its calls have been rejected by the government and the ruling Mozambique Liberation Front (Frelimo) party. The recrimination is threatening widespread instability in a country, where massive gas deposits have recently been discovered. Clashes have erupted between the two sides since April, especially in central province of Sofala, which has a large concentration of armed Renamo forces. Reports by Lusa News Agency say the army has been trying to "deactivate" a Renamo base in Mangomanhe. The number of dead, mainly combatants, is unclear but is estimated to run into dozens. Both sides continue to exchange words on the violence and military mobilization. A Mozambican online newspaper, Verdade, reported on 26 June that number of soldiers and weapons "continue to rise" in the central provinces of Manica and Sofala.
dpcnotes: Tension between gov and RENAMO

notes: We coded DPC in Mozambique in April-October 2013. I tend to think that this is a case of INS and not DPC but I'm not sure. On the one hand, Although RENAMO is currently a political party, the nature of its violent activities in the recent months (ambushes, killing soldiers, kidnapping) seems to me related to INS than DPC (that entails protests, riots, clashes with the police, rallies, etc.) On the other hand, FRELIMO supporters responded with protest and mass demonstrations. There were also violent clashes between RENAMO and FRELIMO supporters.

INS: Ahead of 20 Nov municipal elections, almost 50 people injured during clashes between supporters of ruling party FRELIMO and opposition Mozambique Democratic Movement (MDM) 16 Nov. Preliminary results of 20 Nov vote suggest FRELIMO won landslide; RENAMO boycotted polls, arguing election laws need to be changed. Security forces 1 Nov captured 8 RENAMO gunmen in Rapale district, 10 Nov killed 1 RENAMO gunman in Canda, Nhamadzi administrative post. Number of RENAMO attacks reported during month: RENAMO gunmen 3 Nov attacked truck in Sofala province, 5 Nov wounded 5 in 2 attacks on convoy under military escort, 6 Nov killed 3 soldiers in Gorongosa district, 7 Nov attacked police post and adjacent health centre in Canda, 12 Nov attacked farm in Rapale district, 15 Nov killed 2 people in attack on convoy transiting main N-S highway (crisis watch). reports also in jane's. DPC: Malawian activists are planning a mass protests against the Joyce Banda government in what they call "casual approach" in dealing with the cashgate corruption scandal and also demanding answers on the proceeds of the sale of presidential jet (opensource, Feb 27). Malawi government has maintained its stand that activists [are] working with "foreign elements" to promote instability and an agenda of regime change. On Tuesday [25 February] Brown Mpinganjira, who is minister of information and civic education, in an interview with private-owned Zodiak Broadcasting Services accused the West of bankrolling civil society activists to hold mass protests over the cashgate corruption scandal and reports that proceeds of jet vanished (opensource,  Feb 26). Protest was attended by hundrads (Nyasa Times). I'm not sure if this crosses the threshold of DPC, but let's code 1 and recheck next month.

notes: DPC: Suspected opposition supporters attack Malawi leader's rally. suspected opposition Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) supporters stoned people and smashed car windscreens at a development rally addressed by President Joyce Banda at Goliati Primary School in Senior Chief Chimaliro's area in Thyolo [southern Malawi] on Sunday [16 March] (opensource, March 16).  Violence erupted on Sunday shortly after an election rally led by President Joyce Banda at Goliyati village in a stronghold of her rival Peter Mutharika of the former ruling Democratic Progressive Party. A police officer was axed to death and a protester was shot dead in clashes with stone-throwing opposition activists after police fired tear gas to disperse the hostile crowd. The protester was killed when police fired into the crowd in what a police spokeswoman described as "self defence" (opensource, March 17). Additional reports in opensource.
dpcnotes: opposition supporters attack Malawi leader's rally.

DPC: Some reports of election-related violence and deployment of army to cope with riots. Code 1 and check again next month.                Malawian president Joyce Banda claimed on 22 May the national elections held on 20 May were marred by irregularities and she called for a manual recount of the vote. The Malawi Electoral Commission (MEC) has dismissed President Banda's calls for a recount and denied her allegations. On 22 May, police and soldiers were reportedly sent to the house of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) candidate Peter Mutharika on suspicion of manipulating the vote; however, Mutharika was not arrested and he denies the allegations (jane's intelligence weekly, May 23).  LOCAL civilians set fire to election materials at a polling station and blocked nearby roads in the city of Blantyre in Malawis Southern Region on 20 May, in protest at delays at the polling station during the presidential elections, Al-Jazeera reported. The army was deployed to the area shortly after to quell the protest (jane's). AN ACTIVIST was killed in armed clashes with police forces in the town of Mangochi in Malawis Mangochi district on 30 May, BBC reported. Activists were involved in a protest demanding a recount of the presidential elections (jane's, http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-27645209).  Police fired several rounds of teargas to disperse frustrated voters who vented their anger on electoral staff following delays in starting polling at some centres (opensource, May 21). There is high tension with reports of riots in Malawi's volatile lakeshore district of Mangochi where party supporters are demonstrating for a ballot recount and not results to be announced from the chaotic polls (opensource, May 30).
dpcnotes: Election-related violence

DPC: South Africa's wage bargaining season, or 'strike season', concluded in mid-October, when industrial action in large gold mines, and the construction and automotive sector ended (jane's, Oct 25). TWO people were killed in violent clashes between protesters and police at a demonstration against the standard of municipal services in the town of Bekkersdal in South Africa?s Gauteng province on 24 October, Al-Jazeera reported (jane's). PRO- AFRICAN National Congress (ANC) protesters ran riot in the town of Cape Town in South Africa?s Western Cape Province on 30 October during a demonstration against a purported lack of state housing, looting shops and smashing car windows, but causing no casualties, Reuters reported (jane's). But no reports of widespread protests in SA (jane's, opensource, bbc, guradian) so I coded DPC 0.

DPC: pre-election violence. Mine sector protest.  Police fired baton rounds at a protest staged by the Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) party on 5 November near Union Buildings in Pretoria. The previous day, protest groups threatened more rallies in central Cape Town after demonstrations in October turned into riots triggering looting and property damage. The EFF is headed by an expelled leader of the ruling African National Congress (ANC) party and its supporters have stepped up protests against the ANC in the past month, particularly in Gauteng and Western Cape provinces (jane's). On 14 November, local residents at an Amplats mine in Limpopo damaged five trucks and were dispersed by private security staff, though output was unaffected (jane's). Many reports of violent protests in opensource.             Soooth in October DPC (many reports of riots and protest in late October in jane's and opensource).

notes: DPC: Mine sector protest continued.  Within the platinum sector, the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) is currently on strike at Northam Platinum's Zondereinde Mine, demanding 16% wage increases. AMCU has opted to hold sector-wide action by holding off on separate strike declarations in late 2013 despite receiving certificates of non-resolution at Lonmin, Impala Platinum and Anglo American Platinum. Up to 50% of global platinum production is at risk if a sector-wide strike is called (jane's intelligence weekly, Jan 13). Strikes at South Africa's largest platinum mines will not be resolved in six-week outlook, raising risk of violence (jane's intelligence weekly, Jan 28). (http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-25782493). Protest over water shortages: four people were killed following a protest over water shortages (http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-25840703). TWO people were killed and two others were wounded during a violent clash between police and a group of local residents ? protesting water shortages ? in a village near the town of Brits in South Africa?s North West province on 13 January, Reuters reported. A police spokesman stated that it was not immediately clear whether police had used live ammunition or rubber bullets to quell the protest (jane's).

notes: Historical review of DPC: widespread and persistent DPC until May 2013. In June 2013 until January 2014 there are cases of protest but not widespread enough and not persistnet.                January 2014: FIFTY Saharawi civilians were wounded when security forces dispersed protesters during a demonstration in the city of Laayoune in Morocco?s La?youne-Boujdour-Sakia El Hamra region on 15 January, BBC reported (jane's).               Oct 2013: Nationwide protests have been called in Morocco on 6 October by a group representing the unemployed (jane's).              Sept 2013: Thousands demonstrated in Rabat 22 Sept against govt decision to raise fuel prices (crisis watch). Up to 5,000 people staged a peaceful protest in the Moroccan capital Rabat on 22 September, to protest against the high price of fuel, milk, and meat (jane's).                  Aug 2013: Riot police were deployed in Rabat on 2 August to break up protests by thousands of people over a royal pardon issued to Spanish national, Daniel Galvan Vina, convicted of raping 11 Moroccan children. Other protests occurred in Tangier, Nador, Tetouan, and Kenitra (jane's).                  June 2013: Following King Mohamed VI?s return from 5-week unexplained absence, Istiqlal leader 20 June announced meeting with monarch late June to discuss political crisis stemming from his party?s vote to quit ruling coalition; disaffection of party and population has deepened over range of cuts to popular subsidies, reforms and PM Benkirane?s performance. Some 200 members of pro-reform February 20 protest movement gathered outside justice ministry 5 June to demand release of political prisoners (crisis watch).               May 2013: Authorities continued vigorous crackdown on 20 February movement and unemployed graduate protests; one protester critically wounded 29 May (crisis watch). AT LEAST 20 people were wounded during violent clashes between students and security forces in the city of Fez in Morocco?s F?s-Boulemane region on 7 May, Rue 20 reported. Students were demanded the release of all political prisoners (jane's).

Historical review of DPC: I suggest to smooth away this whole DPC, there is social unrest and cases of protest since June 2013, but not widespread and persistent enough to be coded DPC. no reprots of events related to DPC in crisis watch since June 13. Sep 13: The National Committee for the Defence of the Rights of the Unemployed (Comit? nationale pour la d?fense des droits des ch?meurs: CNDDC) on 28 September held protests in the Algerian capital Algiers and across other provincial capitals nationwide. However, turnout in Algiers on 28 September was small, with reporting from various international and Algerian sources indicating it was probably fewer than a hundred (jane's, Sept 30). Workers at the Algiers Tramway began an open-ended strike on 5 September demanding wage increases (jane's, Sep 6). Aug 13: ONE person was wounded during riots, and subsequent clashes with security forces, in the town of Tadmait in Algeria?s Tizi Ouzou on 11 August, Tour sur l'Alg?rie reported. Rioters were angry over the perceived lack of transparency and inequality regarding the allocation of government aid (jane's). July 13: Unionised workers at Dubai Ports Djazair, the Algerian subsidiary of Dubai Ports World (DP World), said on 17 July that they would go on strike in two weeks' time to demand shorter working hours, better safety conditions, and higher pay (jane's, July 22). June 13: POLICE clashed with protesters demonstrating against government plans to construct a housing cooperative on green space in the city of Tizi Ouzou in Algeria?s Tizi Ouzou province on 17 June, Tout sur l?Algerie reported. No casualties were reported (jane's).                                   ERV in Algenria since Aug 2013  Jan 14: Algerian media reported on 29 January, that 60 people had been arrested since 25 January following rioting in Ghardaia province. There are intermittent outbreaks of communal violence in Ghardaia between Sunni Arabs following the mainstream Maliki school of Islam, and Mozabite Berbers from the minority Ibadi sect (jane's, Jan 30).                                 Dec 13: communal violence - involving looting, burning or vandalism of property and fighting with knives and stones - has persisted in Ghardaia. Since 22 December, 200 civilians and 61 police officers have been injured (jane's, Jan 30). Intercommunal clashes in Gharda?a 25-27 Dec between Cha?mbis (Arabs) and Mozabites (Berbers) left dozens injured, including 40 policemen; govt deployed gendarmerie; president 31 Dec called for calm, dialogue (crisis watch).                            Nov 13: Clashes between Chaambis (Arabs) and Mozabites (Berbers) 24 Nov in Gharda?a wilaya left several injured. Hundreds of villagers east of Tizi Ouzou 7 Nov protested against insecurity (crisis watch).                       Oct 13: Govt 1 Oct deployed security forces in Gharda?a following intercommunal clashes between Cha?mbis (Arabs) and Mozabites (Berbers) (crisis watch). THIRTEEN people were wounded in clashes between residents of rival villages in the Oued Aissi area of Algeria?s Tizi Ouzou province on 10 October, Tout sur l?Algerie reported (jane's).                      Sep 13: no reports.               Aug 13: Clashes between Tuareg Idnan and Berabish Arab tribes in Bordj Badji el-Mokhtar 13-17 Aug left at least 15 dead, 50 injured (crisis watch).                 May 13: AN UNSPECIFIED number of people were wounded during clashes between members of the Arab Chaamba and Berber Mozabties communities in the city of Ghardaia in Algeria?s Ghardaia governorate on 5 May, following three days of clashes, TSA reported (jane's).

notes: DPC: unchecked DPC in January: New constitution signed into law 27 Jan, day after passing National Constituent Assembly vote with 200 of 216 votes. Constitution clears way for new general elections, most secular democratic constitution in Arab world. Radical religious groups criticised secular orientation of constitution; internal tensions in Islamist an-Nahda party over compromises made to achieve breakthrough. PM Jomaa sworn in 10 Jan to replace an-Nahda-led Troika govt; Jomaa?s new caretaker cabinet approved by parliament 29 Jan. Scattered clashes and attempts to attack govt and political parties across country. Some opposition secularists appeared intent on ?de-Islamising? administration, encouraging judges to start trials against an-Nahda ex-ministers over corruption accusations, links to terrorist groups. Protests over economic hardships increased: crowds protested new taxes in Tunis 10 Jan, tens reportedly arrested after clashing with police; same day man killed in clashes near Algerian border after protesters tried to storm customs office (crisis watch).

notes: INS: Continuation of SPLM-N, SLM/A insurgency (Jane's). IN A statement released on 22 January, Sudan Liberation Movement for Justice (SLMJ) spokesman claimed that SLMJ forces seized full control of the garrison and the village of Kalaimendo in the city of Al-Fashir in Sudan?s North Darfur State earlier that same day, Radio Dabanga reported. SLMJ forces also claimed they killed 20 security force members, captured three Land Cruisers mounted with Dushka machineguns, and other small arms. The claims, however, could not be independently substantiated (jane's). Sudan Liberation Movement/Army - Minni Minnawi (SLM/A-Minnawi) militants claimed to have seized the town of GIreida in Sudan?s South Darfur region on 22 January, Radio Dabanga reported. SLM/A-Minnawi claimed that no government forces ?emerged unscathed?. A casualty report was unavailable (jane's). AT LEAST six people were killed during fighting between suspected Sudan Liberation Movement/Army - Minni Minnawi (SLM/A-Minnawi) militants and Sudanese Armed Forces (SAF) at an internally displaced persons (IDP) camp in the Baleel locality of Sudan?s South Darfur State on 10 January, the Sudan Tribune and Radio Dabanga reported (jane's).                             DPC: Ongoing sporadic protests against fuel and bread shortages; finance minister admitted Central Bank facing shortage of hard currency (crisis watch).                               REB: Conflict in Darfur, S Kordofan and Blue Nile continued (crisis watch). Many reports in jane's.                                   ERV: inter-tribal clashes in Darfur. SIX people were killed and at least two others were wounded in inter-tribal armed clashes between Maalia and Rizeigat militiamen in the Khamsat area near the town of Adila in Sudan?s East Darfur State on 24 January, Radio Dabanga reported. The armed clashes were instigated after a group of Rizeigat militiamen stole 45 sheep from the Bakhit area and were tracked down by pro-government Maalia militiamen (jane's). NINE people were killed and six wounded in inter-tribal clashes between members of the Misseriya and Khazam in the town of Deleig in Sudan?s Central Darfur state on 8 January, Radio Dabanga reported. The clash reportedly began following a row over compensation money. No further details were provided (jane's).                             IC: Bashir 6 Jan visited Juba, discussed deploying joint force to protect oilfields in S Sudan. S Sudan opposition forces accused Justice and Equality Movement of fighting alongside S Sudan govt in Unity state (crisis watch)

Army continued arrests of Muslim Brotherhood (MB) leaders, including MB supreme guide Mohammed Badie on charges of inciting violence; govt 17 Aug announced it is engaged in ?war on terror?, considered dissolving MB, however Interim PM Beblawi 27 Aug said would instead monitor group. DPC: 4 killed 20 Feb in clashes in eastern Shiite area, including 2 police. 7 protesters jailed for up to 20 years for demonstrating against govt (crisis watch). While protests have been ongoing in the predominantly Shia villages in the Eastern Province since 2011, small-arms attacks targeting security forces have been isolated and rare. Incidents involving exchanges of fire with security forces have increased in 2014, indicating that militants have improved access to firearms, signalling a growing risk of radical Shia opposition factions resorting to terrorism against the Saudi state. The risk of shooting attacks targeting security forces, government employees and officials, foreign diplomats and expatriates is highest in al-Qatif, al-Awamiyah, Saihat Tarout, and Abha in the oil-rich Eastern Province, but energy production is unlikely to be affected in the next year (jane's intelligence weekly, Feb 27, http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-26275436). I coded these events DPC although it may cross the border into INS/terrorism.

Points of contention reportedly include disagreement over what Soviet era agreements and maps should be used as basis of negotiation. CSTO head 20 Feb said situation along Tajik-Kyrgyz border had improved, however intercommunal violence simmering around Vorukh enclave with series of incidents ratcheting up tensions between ethnic Tajiks and Kyrgyz in area (crisis watch Kyrgyzstan). Tajik and Russian FMs 6 Feb signed protocol on Russian 201st military base in Tajikistan, following over a year of negotiations. Amid continued Collective Security Treaty Organization (CSTO) attempts to reinforce Tajik-Afghan border with military equipment transfers, CSTO head in Dushanbe for talks with President Rahmon 19 Feb. Senior U.S. diplomat visited Tajikistan late Feb to discuss bilateral cooperation, Afghanistan (crisis watch).

IC: Kyrgyz-Tajik border tensions continued: some 60 injured 7 May in mass brawl in Vorukh, Tajik enclave; mob same day attacked Kok-Terek village in Kyrgyzstan, burned vehicles, shops and petrol station; Kyrgyz citizens 9 May blocked Isfara-Vorukh road, accused Tajiks, demanded prosecution of those responsible. Crowds same day gathered in Batken, demanded governors resignation, said if govt fails to resolve border issue residents would do it. Both Tajikistan and Kyrgyzstan govts said they would accelerate border delimitation and demarcation (crisis watch). An incident on 7 May on a section of the Batken-Isfana road, which passes through Tajikistan's exclave of Vorukh in Kyrgyzstan's southern Batken province, resulted in an outbreak of Tajik-Kyrgyz communal violence. At its peak close to 2,000 people fought and threw stones at each other as Kyrgyz and Tajik police struggled to contain the violence. The Tajik rioters burned a gas station, a local store, two Kamaz dump trucks, and three cargo containers in the Kyrgyz village of Kok-Terek. Thirty people were wounded on the Kyrgyz side and 60 on the Tajik side (jane's).  Borderline ERV.

MPs early Feb approved memo on new ownership structure of Kumtor gold mine, proposing equal stake by Kyrgyzstan and Canadian partner in new joint company until 2026 (crisis watch). About 500 people are holding a protest campaign in Issyk-Kul Region's Saruu village [north-eastern Kyrgyzstan] against the detention of activists from their village (opensource, Feb 3). Protest in Kyrgyz north demands closure of Chinese oil refinery (opensource, Feb 17). Anti-gay activists protest against foreign funding of NGOs in Kyrgyzstan (opensource, Feb 27). No repots of violent or widespread protests in country during month.                          REB: Border troops 23 Jan killed 11 alleged Uighur separatists in remote valley in east. Men reportedly entered from China?s Xinjiang province, armed with knives and rifle but no ammunition, said to have murdered Kyrgyz national who apprehended them; authorities claim they were planning to carry out terror attacks in Karakol or Bishkek, refused to surrender (crisis watch). SUSPECTED ethnic Uighur separatist group the Turkistan Islamic Party (TIP) ? also referred to as the East Turkestan Islamic Movement (ETIM) ? on 12 February reportedly sent email to several media outlets in Kyrgyzstan warning of forthcoming attacks targeting Kyrgyz border guards, RFE/RL reported. The threat was made in response to the killing 11 ethnic Uighur by security forces along the Kyrgyz-Chinese border region on 24 January. Preliminary investigations revealed that the message was sent from the town of Hotan in China?s Xinjiang province (jane's). no additional reports.                          IC: Following Jan tensions along Kyrgyz-Tajik border, countries attempted to resolve border demarcation issues around Tajik enclave Vorukh diplomatically with 2 rounds of talks 31 Jan and 14 Feb, but with little progress. Tajik side announced land corridor joining Vorukh to Tajikistan would be created, Kyrgyz side denied; next high-level meeting due March. Points of contention reportedly include disagreement over what Soviet era agreements and maps should be used as basis of negotiation. CSTO head 20 Feb said situation along Tajik-Kyrgyz border had improved, however intercommunal violence simmering around Vorukh enclave with series of incidents ratcheting up tensions between ethnic Tajiks and Kyrgyz in area (crisis watch).
icnotes: Tensions at Kyrgyz-Tajik border

notes: DPC: Govt coalition collapsed 18 March when Ata-Meken pulled out; President?s Social Democratic Party, Ar-Namys and Ata-Meken 31 March agreed to form new coalition. Opposition grouping pulled together by pro-Western independent MP Ravshan Jeenbekov held first conference; leading opposition figures former mayor of Osh Melis Myrzakmatov and Ata-Jurt leader Kamchybek Tashiev did not attend. Former FM Alikbek Jekshenkulov denied involvement in Jeenbekov?s movement. Jeenbekov denied allegations he obtained funds from U.S. govt. Govt late Feb set up new force under interior ministry to deal with pubic unrest. Bishkek police early March outlined formation of local militias to guarantee law and order in event of public unrest (crisis watch). There's definitely political tension, but no reports of mass/violent protest on the gournd (crisis watch, jane's, bbc, guardian, opensource).                            IC: Kyrgyz and Tajik govts reportedly discussing possible land exchanges to resolve longstanding border disputes; following Jan closures, some border checkpoints reportedly reopening (crisis watch). An article by Rustam Kadyrov says that two incidents have taken place on the Kyrgyz-Tajik border. Local journalists were attacked by Tajik nationals, then Kyrgyz people blocked a road in protest against the attack (opensource, March 20). Let's wait another month before smoothing away Jan and Feb 14 IC.

DPC: Amid worsening energy and food insecurity, agriculture minister warned food security at critical point; energy minister 2 April said country will be unable to export energy in 2015 due to low water levels. Opposition protest in capital 10 April passed peacefully; violent anti-mine protest in Talas early April prompted president to visit province. Parliament 16 April approved amendments to criminal code outlawing spreading of false information via media, raising concerns about freedom of press (crisis watch). wait another month for smoothing. IC: Kyrgyz-Tajik border tensions continued: some 60 injured 7 May in mass brawl in Vorukh, Tajik enclave; mob same day attacked Kok-Terek village in Kyrgyzstan, burned vehicles, shops and petrol station; Kyrgyz citizens 9 May blocked Isfara-Vorukh road, accused Tajiks, demanded prosecution of those responsible. Crowds same day gathered in Batken, demanded governors resignation, said if govt fails to resolve border issue residents would do it. Both Tajikistan and Kyrgyzstan govts said they would accelerate border delimitation and demarcation. Kyrgyz parliament committee suggested limiting water supply from Toktogul reservoir to Uzbekistan, risking increased tensions with Uzbekistan (crisis watch). An incident on 7 May on a section of the Batken-Isfana road, which passes through Tajikistan's exclave of Vorukh in Kyrgyzstan's southern Batken province, resulted in an outbreak of Tajik-Kyrgyz communal violence. At its peak close to 2,000 people fought and threw stones at each other as Kyrgyz and Tajik police struggled to contain the violence. The Tajik rioters burned a gas station, a local store, two Kamaz dump trucks, and three cargo containers in the Kyrgyz village of Kok-Terek. Thirty people were wounded on the Kyrgyz side and 60 on the Tajik side (jane's). Borderline ERV.

IC: Jane's: Death of Uzbek border guards could lead to punitive measures: Two Uzbek border guards died as a result of a shootout with their Kyrgyz counterparts on the morning of 23 July. While such shootouts are unlikely to escalate to military confrontations even on a local level, Uzbekistan often cites similar incidents as justification for imposing temporary blockades on people and goods travelling to Kyrgyzstan. However, given that there were two deaths in the latest incident, it is possible that the Uzbek government will also consider additional punitive measures, including shutting off gas deliveries to Kyrgyzstan, as it did on 16 July for payment arrears.

DPC: National bank 11 Feb unexpectedly devalued currency 19%, prompting series of small protests with some arrests, panic buying, run on 3 banks, expectations of price increases. Move generated much public criticism; govt blocked internet petition calling for President Nazarbayev to resign. Column of military vehicles including armoured personal carriers appeared in Almaty 13 Feb; defence ministry said it was test drive. SMS messaging services and apps unavailable same day, observers speculated test of blocking equipment. In 13 Feb media interview Nazarbayev did not rule out seeking presidency again in 2016. In parliament 14 Feb Nazarbayev defended currency devaluation, ordered govt to monitor and control prices for consumer goods and exchange bureaus; threatened to dismiss govt if they fail to attract foreign investment; said pensions and student stipends will be increased by 14% and 10% as of April; also called on 3 major firms to increase salaries 10% (crisis watch). reports also in opensource.

Following Sept meeting between Japanese PM Abe and Chinese President Xi at G20 summit, China declined second meeting at early Oct APEC summit in Bali. China summoned Japanese ambassador in Beijing to express anger after over 100 Japanese MPs 17 Oct visited Yasukuni Shrine honouring WWII dead including war criminals (crisis watch). Accodring to Jane's intelligence weekly: "South China Sea dispute resolution unlikely despite China's diplomatic manoeuvring". It explains that "Sino-ASEAN relations appear to be improving, with high-level visits from Beijing to Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand and Vietnam, and formal consultations on a legally binding Code of Conduct (CoC) for the South China Sea. However, this improvement in diplomatic relations is occurring as China continues to try and enforce its perceived jurisdiction over disputed waters. As such, there appears to be little possibility of a resolution of the South China Sea dispute, even if it may be more peacefully managed and result in an improvement of maritime security in the short term."     I think we should code IC 1 and check again next month.

IC: Disputed Diaoyu/Senkaku island between Japan and China. China 23 Nov created ?East China Sea Air Defence Identification Zone? containing disputed Diaoyu/Senkaku islands, announced defensive measures will be taken against aircraft not obeying Chinese rules; Japan described move as ?escalation?; PM Abe said move ?dangerous?, U.S. called it ?destabilizing?, S Korea also protested. China responded angrily to criticism, lodging complaints with embassies. Japan, S Korea and U.S. all flew military aircraft through area in following days without incident; China 28 Nov sent military aircraft to patrol area. U.S. advised its civilian airlines to observe China?s air defence zone, Japan told its commercial flights to disregard China?s new rules. Japan held joint and combined military drills with U.S. early Nov with 34,000 troops, 6 vessels, 360 aircraft. Abe?s security adviser 6 Nov said Japan should be able to apply its right to fight in collective self-defence to other allies as well as U.S.. Japan scrambled fighter jets after Chinese aircraft sighted near Diaoyu/Senkaku islands 16 Nov; 4 Chinese coast guard vessels sailed near disputed area same day. 180 Japanese businessmen visited Beijing 18-22 Nov to promote economic cooperation. Abe mid Nov visited Cambodia and Laos in bid to strengthen ties (crisis watch).  Unchecked IC.
icnotes: Disputed Diaoyu/Senkaku island between Japan and China

notes: DPC: Political crisis deepened. Awami League (AL) leader/PM Hasina formed ?all-party? interim cabinet to supervise Jan 2014 elections, based on 19 Oct AL proposal to form joint election cabinet with opposition. Ministers submitted resignations 11 Nov, President Abdul Hamid 19 Nov swore in new 8-minister interim govt comprised entirely of pro-AL politicians after 19-party opposition led by Bangladesh National Party (BNP) refused to join, calling it ?another version? of previous AL govt and continuing call for transfer of power to neutral caretaker govt ahead of elections. Opposition 4-7 Nov enforced 84-hour strike to protest new cabinet; clashes with AL-supporters and security forces left 2 dead, over 100 injured. Violence reignited 9 Nov after police arrested 5 senior BNP leaders for ?instigating? attacks. Election Commission 26 Nov announced elections to be held 5 Jan, urged all parties to participate; 28 Nov said elections could be postponed if govt and opposition agree. Opposition rejected date, called for suspension of elections, 26-29 Nov held new strikes and demonstrations; 22 reported killed in unrest and clashes; 30 Nov started another 72-hour nationwide strike demanding postponement of elections. BNP leader Khaleda Zia 20 Nov requested President Hamid resolve political deadlock ?within his constitutional limits?, said opposition would not participate in ?one-sided election? (crisis watch). notes: DPC: Awami League (AL) govt held elections 5 Jan despite boycott by BNP, 18 small parties, sparking further political uncertainty. More than 20 killed in election day violence. Govt claimed voter turnout 48%, some media assessed only 22%, suggesting instances of fraud. 154 of 300 seats contested only by AL candidates. AL won 233 seats; parliamentary opposition to be led by Jatiya Party with 33 seats. BNP absent from parliament for first time since 1991. PM Sheikh Hasina 6 Jan announced crackdown on opposition unrest, but lifted restrictively heavy security around BNP leader Khaleda Zia?s house. Sporadic protests and deadly clashes between opposition supporters and police continued, including 3 killed in clashes with police in SE 26 Jan. Human Rights Watch criticised authorities? use of excessive force, crackdown on opposition, extrajudicial killings by security forces of opposition supporters. Some reports suggesting Hindu minority being increasingly targeted by govt opponents (crisis watch). Many reports in jane's                      ERV: violence aganist Hindus (see above) seem to be a derivative of DPC.                       In general, I think we should code all events in Bangladesh DPC but keep good tabs if this evolves into INS.
dpcnotes: High level of Violence between opposition on the one hand, and police and the Awami-League gov on the other hand.

INS: Series of bomb blasts 11-14 Oct, killing policeman and one other person in Taungoo 11 Oct, and injuring several including in upscale Traders Hotel in Yangon. Several small IEDs also found in various locations. No claim of responsibility; several arrested including suspect in Traders Hotel bombing. Thein Sein 8-10 Oct attended ASEAN Summit, ahead of Myanmar?s (crisis watch). According to Jane's intelligence weekly "It remains unclear whether the bombs were detonated as a warning to the government by one of the various insurgent groups in the country or disgruntled opposition members; or even by elements within the military itself in order to reinforce the importance of the army in the daily affairs of the state. " (Oct 15).    There no indication of who is responsible, so I coulnd't code these events as INS or REB.                           DPC: no reports of widespread protest (crisis watch, jane's, bbc, guardian, opensource).                               REB: Govt and Kachin Independence Organisation (KIO) armed group signed agreement following latest round of peace talks 8-11 Oct; representatives of most other ethnic armed groups attended as observers, also Chinese envoy and UNSG?s Special Adviser for Myanmar. KIO committed to strive to end armed clashes, and reached agreement with army on implementing ceasefire monitoring arrangements and other issues. KIO also expressed support for President?s idea for conference to sign Nationwide Ceasefire Accord with all armed group leaders, possibly in Nov/Dec. Would mean country in peace for first time in 65 years, enshrine govt commitment to next political steps, timeframe. KIO also convened meeting of ethnic armed group leaders at its HQ 30 Oct-1 Nov for discussions ahead of nationwide ceasefire meeting; leaders of Wa armed group, country?s largest, did not attend. Govt 8 Oct released 56 political prisoners, most charged with contacts with ethnic armed groups (crisis watch). There are still reports in Jane's of clashes beteeen KIA militants and the military.   I think we should end this REB in October and not Septmber (in Sept many reports of KIA violence in Jane's). Check again next month.                              ERV: Fresh anti-Muslim violence in Thandwe in Rakhine State early Oct, with attacks on Kaman Muslim minority villages; 7 killed, scores of houses burned down; 78 arrested for role in violence, which coincided with visit by President Thein Sein to area (crisis watch). Reports of ERV in Sep and Oct in jane's database.

ervnotes: Anti-Muslim violence

REB: Unprecedented meeting between leaders of almost all ethnic armed groups hosted by Kachin Independence Organisation (KIO) at their Laiza HQ 30 Oct-2 Nov followed by meeting in Kachin State capital Myitkyina between armed group leaders and govt 3-5 Nov. Discussed draft text for Nationwide Ceasefire Accord; no final agreement, but parties agreed to follow-up meeting in Karen State capital in Dec; govt still hopes to hold nationwide ceasefire signing ceremony early 2014. Senior KIO leader General Gun Maw visited Yangon mid-Nov for talks with Myanmar Peace Centre and Kachin community leaders, gave public speech, in govt-approved visit (crisis watch). Jane's analyzes the situation as follows: "Following months of uncertainty, early November saw Myanmar's ethnic Bamar-dominated government and a joint body representing the majority of the country's ethnic armed groups (EAGs) commit to the implementation of a nationwide ceasefire accord. However, talks also brought to the surface seemingly irreconcilable discords over what such an agreement would entail, following a surprise change in position by the government. Though both sides remain committed to progress towards a national ceasefire, the parties are likely to reach a stalemate, unless significant concessions can be made by either side. Without such  progress, violence is almost certain to continue in numerous regions, especially in Kachin State." (jane's intelligence weekly, Nov 19). Some reports of violent clashes with KIA militants (jane's).     I think we should keep REB 0 and check again next month to see if violence resumed.                                      ERV: Fighting flared in Mansi township, Kachin State in recent weeks, displacing several hundred civilians. Rakhine State authorities late Oct brought charges against 61 people (out of 78 initially arrested), majority Buddhists, for various offences including murder in relation to anti-Muslim violence in Thandwe town. OIC delegation visited Myanmar, including Rakhine State, to see situation of Muslims affected by communal violence. EU delegation led by foreign policy chief Catherine Ashton also visited (crisis watch). Some reports of protests (opensource) - a derivative of ERV.

notes: REB: Govt peace negotiators and armed group representatives met in Yangon 9-10 March, reached agreement to work on consolidated ceasefire accord text, established joint drafting group comprising 9 members from ethnic armed groups and 9 from govt (3 each from executive, legislature and military) (crisis watch). SEVEN ethnic Red Shan people ? including a teacher and a Shan Nationalities Democratic Party (SNDP) activist - were kidnapped by suspected Kachin Independence Army (KIA) militants from the Pansatt village of the district of Bhamo in Myanmar?s Kachin State on 11 March, DVB reported (jane's). no additional reports.  Smooth away Feb REB                                       ERV: Controversial UN/donor-backed census began 30 March amid fears of intercommunal violence in Rakhine state, as Rakhine nationalists threatened to boycott census over issue of people being allowed to self-identify ethnicity as Rohingya; called off boycott after govt 29 March decided to prevent people self-identifying as Rohingya. Protests in Rakhine state mid-month against census, escalated to attacks on offices and homes of international humanitarian workers 26-27 March; 1 bystander killed by police warning shot; some 100 humanitarian staff evacuated to Yangon. Commission established by President Thein Sein to investigate allegations of killings of Rohingya villagers in Du Chee Yar Tan village in Maungdaw submitted report to President 28 Feb, finding no evidence to support allegations; also recommended addressing status of Rohingya in Rakhine State, granting citizenship to those who meet criteria under restrictive 1982 law. President late Feb, responding to letter with over 1 million signatures received from monk-led campaign, requested legislature to consider enacting legislation that would restrict inter-faith marriage, conversion from one religion to another, polygamy and number of children, likely to be targeted at Muslim/Rohingya communities. President 7 March appointed commission charged with drafting 2 bills on conversion and balancing population by 30 June; requested legislature to take lead on drafting the other 2 bills, in consultation with Supreme Court. Moves prompted condemnation by rights groups (crisis watch).

notes: REB: Govt, Kachin Independence Organisation leaders met 13 May for bilateral talks following April clashes; representatives of other ethnic groups, UN, China attended as observers: agreement reached on establishing joint conflict resolution committee. Another round of multilateral peace talks between govt, various armed groups held 19-21 May. Enumeration period for controversial census extended to 10 June to reach populations in Kachin, Rakhine states. Opposition NLD, 88 Generation group held series of joint rallies across country pushing for constitutional change (crisis watch). ARMED clashes between army forces and Kachin Independence Army (KIA) militants erupted in the Kyauk Pya area on the Bham-Namhkham road in Myanmars Kachin state on 8 May, BNI Online reported. Armed clashes were instigated when KIA militants attacked a convoy of 14 army vehicles carrying rations and military supplies in the area. There were no reported casualties (jane's). FOUR police officers were killed and another was wounded in an ambush by suspected Rohingya Solidarity Organisation (RSO) militants near the village of Bandoola in Maungdaw-Myoma district, near the border with Bangladesh, in Myanmars Rakhine state on 17 May, Eleven Myanmar reported. Reinforcements reportedly arrived and forced the militants to flee over the border into Bangladesh. Two police officers were reported as missing following the ambush (jane's). THE border outpost 38 was attacked by suspected Rohingya Solidarity Organization (RSO) militants in the Maugdaw district of Myanmars Rakhine state on 12 May, Eleven reported. A casualty report was unavailable.                            ERV: no reports of Buddhist-Muslim violence (crisis watch, jane's, )

Govt won easy victory in western and southern provincial council elections 29 March, though with reduced majorities; President Rajapaksa, other govt candidates used HRC process and threat of ?international intervention? to win votes, sharply criticised Tamil National Alliance (TNA) for supporting HRC resolution. Govt launched military and police crackdown in N and E, alleging attempt to revive LTTE; increased pressure on human rights activists and NGOs, accused of propagating ?false information? to tarnish govt?s image internationally. 6 activists arrested, others threatened mid-March; 2 activists held 48 hours under Prevention of Terrorism Act released 16 March following international outcry. Attacks reflect insurgency?s shift to focus on security forces in recent months. DPC: Cabinet 9 Oct approved imposition of Internal Security Act (ISA) for 3 Bangkok districts in response to protest by People?s Democratic Force To Overthrow Thaksin. Larger protests anticipated following 18 Oct revision by governing Pheu Thai Party of draft bill to provide amnesty for offences related to political unrest since 2006, in apparent bid to allow exiled former PM Thaksin Shinawatra to return without serving 2-year sentence for abuse of power. Revised bill angered Thaksin opponents plus some pro-Thaksin Red Shirts, as it would absolve former PM Abhisit Vejjajiva and deputy of causing deaths by ordering 2010 crackdown on anti-govt protesters (crisis watch). UNIDENTIFIED assailants threw several incendiary devices at members of the People?s Army Against Thaksin Regime protest movement at the Urupong Expressway in the Thai capital Bangkok early on 11 October (jane's).  A red-shirt group says it will mobilize 10,000 people to oppose the government's blanket amnesty bill. More than 200 red-shirt activists led by the Red Sunday Group gathered in central Bangkok on 27 October to express their dissatisfaction with the bill, which seeks to grant amnesty to all involved in political unrest since the 19 September 2006 coup, including protest leaders, soldiers, and authorities (opensource, Oct 28). Additional reports of low and middle scale protest in opensource.                            REB: Violence in southernmost provinces included 4 soldiers killed in IED attack targeting teacher-escort patrol in Krong Pinang District, Yala 3 Oct. 2 rangers killed in IED attack in Rangae District, Narathiwat, 11 Oct. Insurgents 9 Oct detonated 27 small IEDs at banks and shops in Narathiwat, Pattani, Yala and Songkhla provinces, 3 injured; army ranger killed, 4 wounded in IED attack in Cho Airong District, Narathiwat Province same day; teacher executed in Saiburi District, Pattani. 3 killed in gun battle between security forces and suspected militants in Thung Yang Daeng District, Pattani, 15 Oct (crisis watch).
dpcnotes: Anti-regime protest
rebnotes: separatist militarism in the south

DPC: Bangkok saw largest protests since 2010 with anti-govt protesters occupying ministries and govt buildings late month in bid to oust elected Pheu Thai Party (PTP)-led govt of PM Yingluck Shinawatra. Lower House 1 Nov passed a blanket amnesty bill that would allow exiled former PM Thaksin Shinawatra to return and absolve opposition Democrat Party leaders for role in 2010 crackdown-related deaths. Bill sparked wave of protests, led by Democrat MP Suthep Thaugsuban, swelling into movement to eradicate ?Thaksin regime?. Senate 11 Nov rejected amnesty bill. Suthep and 8 other Democrat MPs announced resignation in order to lead protests. Constitutional Court 20 Nov ruled Sept amendment to establish all-elected Senate unconstitutional, dismissed petition to dissolve PTP. Anti-govt rallies reignited 23 Nov. Under banner of Civil Movement for Democracy (CMD), protesters 25 Nov occupied foreign and finance ministries. Cabinet 25 Nov invoked Internal Security Act in Bangkok and neighbouring provinces, court issued arrest warrant for Suthep. CDM protesters 26-27 Nov surrounded other ministries and govt buildings, 29 Nov stormed army HQ, 1 Dec attempted to breach security barriers at Govt House; police responded with tear gas. At least 2 killed, dozens injured in protest-related violence 30 Nov. Thousands of Red Shirts gathered in Bangkok stadium in support of govt. PM Yingluck 28 Nov survived vote of no confidence 297-134, said no early election (crisis watch).                          REB: National Security Council chief Lt Gen Paradorn Pattanatabutr 27 Nov said next round of dialogue between govt and Barisan Revolusi Nasional (BRN) early Dec, postponed due to political turmoil. Deep South Watch reported 32 deaths, 72 wounded in 118 incidents in Oct in main conflict areas, mostly due to bombings. Gunmen shot dead village headman in Narathiwat?s Muang District 7 Nov. Motorcycle bomb exploded in Rangae 7 Nov, killing 2 soldiers, wounding 6 others. Bomb injured 4 police, 8 civilians in Waeng District, Narathiwat, 13 Nov. IED attack wounded 3 rangers in Mae Kaen District, Pattani 14 Nov. Gunmen killed off-duty ranger in Muang District, Pattani, 19 Nov (crisis watch).
dpcnotes: Anti-regime protest
rebnotes: separatist militarism in the south

DPC: Political turmoil intensified as People?s Democratic Reform Committee (PDRC) 13 Jan began series of protests aiming to ?shut down Bangkok?, stepping up efforts to overthrow PM Yingluck?s caretaker govt and force cancellation of 2 Feb general election; further violence anticipated on election day. Protest-related violence increased, including 1 killed, 35 injured in grenade attack on PDRC march 17 Jan; dozens injured by 2 grenades at PDRC?s Victory Monument protest site 19 Jan. Govt imposed state of emergency in Bangkok and surrounding provinces beginning 22 Jan. Amid deteriorating security, pressure growing on govt to delay poll, including repeated calls from Election Commission. Constitutional Court 24 Jan ruled govt could postpone poll; govt 28 Jan said election will take place as scheduled. Anti-govt protesters 26 Jan turned out at polling stations to prevent people from advance voting; protest leader and former New Politics Party politician Suthin Tharatinwas shot dead outside polling station in SE Bangkok. United Front for Democracy Against Dictatorship (main Red Shirt organisation) 26 Jan said Red Shirts will enter Bangkok within hours if election is postponed (crisis watch).                                REB: Ongoing violence in southernmost provinces included: 1 ranger killed, 5 injured in 2 bomb attacks in Narathiwat Province 21 Jan; Buddhist monk, ranger and civilian killed in 2 separate attacks in Pattani province 24 Jan; IED blast killed 2 police and injured 3 in Than To District, Yala same day (crisis watch).
dpcnotes: Anti-regime protest
rebnotes: separatist militarism in the south

notes: DPC: Army 22 May staged coup after months of political unrest, violence and large-scale demonstrations: suspended constitution; dismissed caretaker govt; arrested hundreds of politicians including former PM Yingluck, democracy activists and journalists. Several released under orders to remain in country, not oppose coup. Coup followed army chief Gen Prayuth Chan-ochas announcement of nationwide martial law 20 May: military shut down broadcasts from partisan TV and radio stations, disbanded govts temporary security centre, instructed all protesters to remain peaceful. Prayuth 26 May said formally recognised as head of National Council for Peace and Order (NCPO) by King, warned force will be used in case of renewed protests. Junta ordered military tribunal to try l?se majest? and national-security cases. Hundreds of anti-coup protesters rallied daily in Bangkok late month, in defiance of martial law but without serious violence. Prayuth 30 May said 15 months of reform, reconciliation needed before general elections. Ahead of army intervention, Constitutional Court 7 May removed caretaker PM Yingluck Shinawatra and 9 cabinet ministers for abuse of power; governing Pheu Thai Party called court ruling judicial coup. National Anti-Corruption Commission 8 May voted to impeach Yingluck. Widespread pro- and anti-govt protests early month: 3 killed, over 20 injured 15 May in grenade and shooting attack on anti-govt protesters in central Bangkok (crisis watch).                                            REB: Violence in south continued with several insurgent attacks including: 2 bombs detonated 6 May in Hat Yai city, 2 police and 6 civilians injured; coordinated attacks across Narathiwat and Yala provinces 11 May, 1 dead and 9 injured; 10 injured 28 May in bombing at Khok Pho Hospital, Pattani (crisis watch).
dpcnotes: Severe internal crisis, protest and military coup
rebnotes: separatist militarism in the south

notes: DPC: THREE female protesters were wounded during violent clashes with police personnel in the Prampi Makara district of the Cambodian capital Phnom Penh on 17 October, the Phnom Penh Post reported (jane's). The opposition Cambodia National Rescue Party (CNRP) has called for a nationwide general strike to press its demands for an independent investigation into the disputed July election results (jane's, Oct 2). The first of the three-day mass demonstrations organized by the opposition Cambodia National Rescue Party (CNRP) went without any violence amid tight security.  Different Cambodian media reports have put the number of protesters at between 5,000 and 20,000, but only 1,000 of them were allowed by the Ministry of Interior to join a march the CNRP leader Sam Rainsy led after the protest to the offices of the United Nations and various foreign embassies in Phnom Penh, where he submitted the CNRP's petitions for international intervention in Cambodia's political stalemate. During a press conference on 23 October, Sam Rainsy also said this new round of mass protests is aimed at instigating electoral reforms to prevent all the alleged irregularities found during the July election from happening again, not to result in "power sharing" between the government and the opposition (opensource, Oct 24).

notes: DPC: A 49-year-old bystander was killed when she was hit by a stray bullet fired by police during clashes with hundreds of protesting garment workers in Cambodia?s capital Phnom Penh on 12 November, The Nation reported. Three other people were wounded during the clashes (jane's, http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-24910835). Cambodia: Opposition CNRP Party To Organize Two Anti-Government Demonstrations in December    Cambodia's opposition has scheduled two mass demonstrations for next month following a bloody clash between garment workers and security forces last week and ahead of an ultimatum set by the Cambodia National Rescue Party (CNRP) for dialogue with the government, a party spokesperson has said. Opposition lawmaker Mu Sochua said the first demonstration would be held in Freedom Park on 10 December to demand an investigation into the death of 49-year-old street vendor Eng Sokhum, who was killed when police opened fire on protesters from the SL Garment factory after they charged a police line on 12 November. CNRP president Sam Rainsy, however, said that the protest ? due to be held on UN Human Rights Day ? would be "for all people who have suffered human rights abuses" in the country. The second demonstration, Sochua added, would be larger, last for longer than one day and include marches through the capital's streets in a similar vein to a mass rally held in August (opensource, Southeast Asia Snapshot 20 November 2013).
dpcnotes: Garments worker protest. Opposition organizing rallies in Dec.

IC: AT LEAST 21 people  including five steel plant workers - were killed during violent anti-China riots targeting the Taiwanese-owned Formosa Plastics Group steel plant in an unspecified location in Vietnams Ha Tinh province on 14 May, Reuters reported. Anti-China riots have taken place in several provinces since 13 May following protests against Beijing placing an oil rig in a part of the South China Sea which Hanoi purports to claim (jane's). A Vietnamese fishing boat has sunk after it collided with a Chinese vessel near a controversial oil rig in the South China Sea, amid tensions between the two nations (May 27, bbc, http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-27583564). China ships evacuate Vietnam workers after protests (May 19, bbc, http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-27467450). At least 15 foreign-owned factories were set on fire and hundreds more attacked by thousands of protesters at two industrial parks in southern Vietnam on Tuesday. The protests came after China moved a drilling rig into South China Sea waters also claimed by Vietnam earlier this month. Despite the riots, China says its oil rig will continue drilling (May 16, bbc, http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-27435898). Additional reports in all source.

notes: REB: Continued uptick in violence; 8 killed by bomb in Cotabato City, Mindanao 5 Aug; 3 bombings in central Mindanao 7 Aug, with targets including army truck. Bangsamoro Islamic Freedom Movement (BIFM) claimed responsibility for latter. Police 6 Aug filed murder charges against suspects in 26 July Cagayan de Oro bombing, including member of new Khilafah Islamic Movement, which officials claim has links with foreign jihadis. President Aquino 8 Aug suggested BIFM, Abu Sayyaf Group (ASG) and other new radical group perpetrating recent attacks to derail Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) peace process. Clashes between BIFM and Philippine military 10-13 Aug displaced almost 10,000 villagers in 2 towns in N Cotabato province. Govt-MILF peace talks resumed mid-Aug, with 2 of 4 annexes to Oct 2012 pact left to negotiate. In Sulu archipelago, some 70 members of ASG and military clashed in Basilan 8 Aug; 1 soldier, 7 militants killed. 2 injured by bomb in Jolo town 14 Aug; military blamed ASG (crisis watch).
